{"title_page": "Polistes bahamensis", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Polistes bahamensis (29993770975).jpg\n|genus = Polistes\n|species = bahamensis \n|authority = ([[Joseph Charles Bequaert|Bequaert]] & [[:species:George Salt|Salt]], 1931)\n|synonyms =\n*''Polistes bahamensis'' var. ''bahamensis'' <small>Bequaert & Salt, 1931</small>\n*''Polistes bahamensis'' var. ''bilineolatus'' <small>Bequaert & Salt, 1931</small>\n*''Polistes bahamensis'' var. ''picturatus'' <small>Bequaert & Salt, 1931</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' var. ''bahamensis'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Bequaert, 1940</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' var. ''bilineolatus'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Bequaert, 1940</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' var. ''picturatus'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Bequaert, 1940</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' var. ''louisianus'' <small>Bequaert, 1940</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' ssp. ''bahamensis'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) [[Owain Richards|Richards]], 1978</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' ssp. ''bilineolatus'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Richards, 1978</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' ssp. ''picturatus'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Richards, 1978</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' ssp. ''louisianus'' <small>(Bequaert, 1940) Richards, 1978</small>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=GBIF>{{Cite web |title=''Polistes bahamensis'' Bequaert & Salt, 1931 |url=https://www.gbif.org/species/1310634 |website=GBIF |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Kons2017b>{{cite web |url=http://www.lepidopterabiodiversity.com/Vespidae/CL/bahamensis.htm |title=''Polistes instabilis'' (or species near) specimen images in A Preliminary Illustrated Check List of the Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |last=Kons |first=Hugo L. Jr. |last2=Rowan |first2=Rex |date=2017 |website=The Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |publisher=Lepidoptera Biodiversity LLC |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Snelling1983>{{cite journal |last=Snelling |first=Roy R. |author-link=Roy |date=1983 |title=Taxonomic and nomenclatural studies on American polistine wasps (Hymenoptera: Vespidae) |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/56199405 |journal=Pan-Pacific Entomologist |volume=59 |issue=1\u20144 |pages=267\u2014269 |doi= |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Polistes bahamensis''''' is a large [[species]] of colourful [[paper wasp]] in the genus ''[[Polistes]]'' of the family [[Vespidae]] which occurs in the [[Bahamas]], [[Florida]] and [[Louisiana]].<ref name=GBIF/><ref name=BugGuide>{{cite web |url=https://bugguide.net/node/view/87100 |title=Species ''Polistes bahamensis'' |last=Bentley |first=Tom |last2=Moisset |first2=Beatriz |date=2 February 2009 |website=BugGuide.Net |publisher=Department of Entomology, [[Iowa State University]] |access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref> It is also said to occur in [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref name=BugGuide/><ref name=narod>{{cite web |url=http://vespabellicosus2008.narod.ru/pdf6.pdf |title=Distributional Checklist of Species of the Genus ''Polistes'' (Hymenoptera: Vespidae; Polistinae, Polistini) }}</ref> \n\n==Taxonomy==\nIt was first described as an [[endemic]] new species from the Bahamas by [[Joseph Charles Bequaert]] and [[:species:George Salt|George Salt]] in 1931, consisting of three [[Variety_(botany)#Other_nomenclature_uses|varieties]] based on geography and patterns of coloured markings, ''P. bahamensis'' var. ''bahamensis'', ''P. bahamensis'' var. ''bilineolatus'' and ''P. bahamensis'' var. ''picturatus''. The [[Subspecies#Nominate subspecies|nominate]] variety of ''bahamensis'' was reported to be an [[endemic]] of [[Andros Island]], var. ''bilineolatus'' was only found in the central islands of [[New Providence Island|New Providence]] and [[Eleuthera]], and var. ''picturatus'' was known from [[Acklins]], [[Mariguana]], [[Rum Cay]], [[Crooked Island, Bahamas|Crooked Island]], [[Long Island, Bahamas|Long Island]], [[Watlings Island]] and [[Cat Island, Bahamas|Cat Island]].<ref name=Bequaert1931>{{cite journal |last=Bequaert |first=Joseph Charles |author-link=Joseph Charles Bequaert |last2=Salt |first2=George |author-link2=species:George Salt |date=1 December 1931 |title=New West Indian Diploptera |url=https://digitalcommons.usu.edu/bee_lab_ba/281/ |journal=Annals of the Entomological Society of America |volume=24 |issue=4 |pages=765\u2014797 |doi=10.1093/aesa/24.4.765 |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Bequaert1940>{{cite journal |last=Bequaert |first=Joseph Charles |author-link=Joseph Charles Bequaert |date=1940 |title=An Introductory Study of ''Polistes'' in the United States and Canada with Descriptions of Some New North and South American Forms (Hymenoptera; Vespid\u00e6) |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/50711500 |journal=Journal of the New York Entomological Society |volume=48 |pages=14 |doi= |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Snelling1955>{{cite journal |last=Snelling |first=Roy R. |author-link=Roy Snelling |date=14 January 1955 |title=Notes on some ''Polistes'' in the American Museum of Natural History, with descriptions of new North American subspecies (Hymenoptera, Vespidae) |url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/4730//v2/dspace/ingest/pdfSource/nov/N1701.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |journal=American Museum Novitates |volume=1701 |pages=4\u20148 |doi= |access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> In 1940 Bequaert subsumed the species and its three varieties under [[Polistes exclamans|''P. exclamans'']], as well as described another new variety in that species, ''P. exclamans'' var. ''louisianus'', from three female specimens caught in [[New Orleans]].<ref name=Bequaert1940/><ref name=Snelling1955/> \n\nIn 1955 the variety ''louisianus'' was [[synonym (taxonomy)|synonymised]] with ''P. exclamans'' ''[[sensu stricto]]'' by [[Roy Snelling]], who stated that after examining large amounts of the wasps from two nests recovered in New Orleans, the vast majority of the individual wasps were typical nominate forms of ''exclamans'', with only one or two individuals per nest displaying the colour patterns (reduced yellow markings) reported by Bequaert in 1940, and he furthermore states that he collected a single ''louisianus'' wasp in a very large colony of ''P. exclamans'' var. ''exclamans'' in [[Kansas]]. Snelling also expanded the distribution of the taxon outside of the Bahamas by reporting on the presence of ''P. exclamans'' var. ''bahamensis'' in southern Florida, stating some, but not all, of the 21 wasps collected in the Royal Palm State Park, a wooded grove which has now become the nucleus of [[the Everglades]], and the nearby [[Archbold Biological Station]] were somewhat different in colouration with ''bahamensis'', but that the collection of specimens as a whole integrated seamlessly with the colour pattern of insular specimens. Snelling continued to recognise the ''P. exclamans'' varieties ''bilineolatus'' and ''picturatus'' as Bahamanian endemics.<ref name=Snelling1955/> \n\nBequaert and Salt's three or four varieties were then treated as [[subspecies]] of ''P. exclamans'' by [[Owain Richards]] in 1978.<!--need verification in primary source--> \n\n[[Karl Vorse Krombein]] was apparently the first to associate the variety ''louisianus'' with ''P. exclamans'' var. ''bahamensis'' in 1979, attributing the synonymy to Snelling.<ref name=Krombein1979>{{cite book |last=Krombein |first=Karl Vorse |author-link=Karl Vorse Krombein |chapter=Vespoidea |chapter-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4575572 |editor1-last=Krombein |editor1-first=Karl V. |editor2-last=Hurd |editor2-first=Paul D. Jr. |editor3-last=Smith |editor3-first=David R. |editor4-last=Burks |editor4-first=B. D. |date=1979 |title=Catalog of Hymenoptera in America North of Mexico |volume=2 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4575673 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |page=1510\u20141515 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.5074}}</ref> In 1983 Snelling chose to re-recognise ''P. bahamensis'' as a valid species again, and while doing so synonymised the subspecies ''bilineolatus'' and ''picturatus'' and \"reiterated\" his conclusion regarding the variety ''louisianus'' -although by 1983 he was stating that he had synonymised it with ''bahamensis'' in 1955 instead of ''P. exclamans'' var. ''exclamans''. By recognising the New Orleans specimens as ''bahamensis'' in 1983, Snelling effectively expanded the known distribution of this taxon hundreds of kilometres down the coast of the [[Gulf of Mexico]].<ref name=Snelling1983/> As of 2017 Kons and Rowan consider that all or at least part of the US population should be split off into a separate species, ''P. louisianus''; -these writers believe that many ''Polistes'' species should be split into numerous [[sympatric]] species based on small differences in their body colour.<ref name=Kons2017b/><ref name=Kons2017>{{cite web |url=http://www.lepidopterabiodiversity.com/Vespidae/CL/bahamensis.htm |title=''Polistes bahamensis'' specimen images in A Preliminary Illustrated Check List of the Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |last=Kons |first=Hugo L. Jr. |last2=Rowan |first2=Rex |date=2017 |website=The Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |publisher=Lepidoptera Biodiversity LLC |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Etymology===\nThe [[etymology]] of the [[specific epithet]] ''bahamensis'' is from the place 'the Bahamas', combined with the [[Latin language|Latin]] [[suffix]] [[:wikt:-ensis#Suffix|''-ensis'']], meaning 'of, or from, (a place)' or 'pertaining to', together forming an adjective with the meaning: 'of the Bahamas'.\n\n==Description==\nThe identification of this species has always been very difficult. When Bequaert first examined the first three specimens from New Orleans around 1940, he at first thought them to be perhaps [[Polistes crinitus|''P. crinitus'']] or [[Polistes versicolor|''P. versicolor'']] introduced from the [[Caribbean]].<ref name=Bequaert1940/> Snelling examined the same population and classified it as ''P. exclamans'' var. ''exclamans'' in 1955.<ref name=Snelling1955/>\n\nIt has also been seen as very similar to [[Polistes annularis|''P. annularis'']], with which it shares a slender first [[metasoma]]l segment. It can be distinguished from this species by the yellow spot on the [[mesopleuron]], and almost always having a yellow apical band on the posterior (back) margin of the [[tergum|tergites]] and more developed yellow markings on the mesosoma.<ref name=BugGuide/>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe known range has expanded as certain populations of wasps were determined to be this species, and with the collection of more specimens. \n\n===Bahamas===\nThe first specimens were first collected on [[New Providence Island]] in 1909. Bequaert and Salt described the species in 1931 from specimens collected on [[Acklins]], [[Andros Island]], [[Cat Island, Bahamas|Cat Island]], [[Crooked Island, Bahamas|Crooked Island]], [[Eleuthera]], [[Long Island, Bahamas|Long Island]], [[Mariguana]], New Providence Island, [[Rum Cay]] and [[Watlings Island]].<ref name=Bequaert1931/><ref name=Bequaert1940/><ref name=Snelling1955/> Specimens were first collected on [[Mayaguana]] in 1996, and the reported range was extended further to [[Great Inagua]] in 2011, with the species now believed to occur on all the major islands of the Bahamas,<ref name=Starr2011>{{cite journal |last=Starr |first=Christopher K. |last2=Sewlal |first2=Jo-Anne N. |date=2011 |title=A Range Extension of the Social Wasp ''Polistes bahamansis'' (Hymenoptera: Vespidae) |url=https://uwispace.sta.uwi.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/2139/13082/2011-P.BAHAMENSIS.pdf;sequence=1 |journal=International Journal of Bahamian Studies |volume=17 |issue=2 |pages=1\u20142 |doi= |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===USA===\nSnelling first extended the range of this species to southern [[Florida]] when he identified a group of specimens of wasps collected there since the late 1930s as belonging to this species in a 1955 article. The ''louisianus'' colour form described by Bequaert in 1940, considered a synonym of the nominate taxon of ''P. exclamans'' by Snelling at the time, was initially only known from [[New Orleans]], but Snelling also described having seen a single individual in a nest of ''P. exclamans'' in [[Kansas]].<ref name=Snelling1955/> The taxon is included in the 1979 ''Catalog of Hymenoptera in America north of Mexico'', which for some reason does not include endemic varieties found in the Bahamas as found in America north of Mexico, as a subspecies of ''P. exclamans''. In this work ''louisianus'' is considered a synonym of ''P. exclamans'' var. ''bahamensis'', and the distribution is given as from \"Louisiana to Florida\".<ref name=Krombein1979/>\n\nSnelling reported the presence of this taxon in the USA again in 1983, stating its range included Florida, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] and [[Louisiana]].<ref name=BugGuide/><ref name=Kons2017/> A photograph of a number of wasps building a nest in coastal [[North Carolina]] in 2017 has been identified as being of this species.<ref name=GBIF/>\n\n==Ecology==\nIt has usually been recorded nesting under [[eaves]] of roofs of buildings<ref name=Starr2011/><ref name=Kons2018nests>{{cite web |url=http://www.lepidopterabiodiversity.com/Vespidae/AppendixB.htm |title=APPENDIX B: Nest Mate Associations of Florida Polistinae Species |last=Kons |first=Hugo L. Jr. |last2=Rowan |first2=Rex |date=2018 |website=The Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |publisher=Lepidoptera Biodiversity LLC |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> and sometimes under palm fronds.<ref name=BugGuide/><ref name=Starr2011/> The nest is suspended from an attachment stalk known as a [[Petiole_(insect_anatomy)#Other uses|petiole]].<ref name=Starr2011/>\n\nAs of 2017, no [[Strepsiptera]]n parasites are reported for ''P. bahamensis''.<ref name=Kons2018Strepsi>{{cite web |url=http://www.lepidopterabiodiversity.com/Vespidae/AppendixI.htm |title=APPENDIX I: Stylopized Florida Polistinae |last=Kons |first=Hugo L. Jr. |last2=Rowan |first2=Rex |date=2018 |website=The Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |publisher=Lepidoptera Biodiversity LLC |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\nIt is quite common in the centre of its range, such as on New Providence Island, especially in urban areas such as the capital city [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]]. In common with most species, the abundance diminishes at the edges of its distribution, being quite rare on Great Inagua and Mayaguana and \"sporadic\" along the Gulf Coast of Florida.<ref name=Starr2011/>\n\nThe [[IUCN]] has [[not evaluated]] this species' [[Conservation_status#IUCN_Red_List_of_Threatened_Species|conservation status]].<ref name=GBIF/>\n\nIt has been recorded as present in the following [[protected areas]]:\n*[[Archbold Biological Station]], [[Lake Placid, Florida|Lake Placid]], [[Highlands County, Florida|Highlands County]], Florida, USA.<ref name=Snelling1955/>\n*[[Emeralda Marsh Conservation Area]], [[Lake County, Florida|Lake County]], Florida, USA.<ref name=BugGuide/>\n*[[Inagua National Park]], Great Inagua, the Bahamas.<ref name=Starr2011/>\n*[[Everglades National Park]], Florida, USA.<ref name=Snelling1955/>\n*[[Watermelon Pond Wildlife Management Area]], [[Alachua County, Florida|Alachua County]], Florida, USA.<ref name=Kons2018nests/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q14422670}}\n\n[[Category:Polistes|bahamensis]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1931]]\n\n\n{{Vespidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Polistes bahamensis (29993770975).jpg\n|genus = Polistes\n|species = bahamensis \n|authority = ([[Joseph Charles Bequaert|Bequaert]] & [[:species:George Salt|Salt]], 1931)\n|synonyms =\n*''Polistes bahamensis'' var. ''bahamensis'' <small>Bequaert & Salt, 1931</small>\n*''Polistes bahamensis'' var. ''bilineolatus'' <small>Bequaert & Salt, 1931</small>\n*''Polistes bahamensis'' var. ''picturatus'' <small>Bequaert & Salt, 1931</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' var. ''bahamensis'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Bequaert, 1940</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' var. ''bilineolatus'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Bequaert, 1940</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' var. ''picturatus'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Bequaert, 1940</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' var. ''louisianus'' <small>Bequaert, 1940</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' ssp. ''bahamensis'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) [[Owain Richards|Richards]], 1978</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' ssp. ''bilineolatus'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Richards, 1978</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' ssp. ''picturatus'' <small>(Bequaert & Salt, 1931) Richards, 1978</small>\n*''Polistes exclamans'' ssp. ''louisianus'' <small>(Bequaert, 1940) Richards, 1978</small>\n|synonyms_ref = <ref name=GBIF>{{Cite web |title=''Polistes bahamensis'' Bequaert & Salt, 1931 |url=https://www.gbif.org/species/1310634 |website=GBIF |accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Kons2017b>{{cite web |url=http://www.lepidopterabiodiversity.com/Vespidae/CL/bahamensis.htm |title=''Polistes instabilis'' (or species near) specimen images in A Preliminary Illustrated Check List of the Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |last=Kons |first=Hugo L. Jr. |last2=Rowan |first2=Rex |date=2017 |website=The Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |publisher=Lepidoptera Biodiversity LLC |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Snelling1983>{{cite journal |last=Snelling |first=Roy R. |author-link=Roy |date=1983 |title=Taxonomic and nomenclatural studies on American polistine wasps (Hymenoptera: Vespidae) |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/56199405 |journal=Pan-Pacific Entomologist |volume=59 |issue=1\u20144 |pages=267\u2014269 |doi= |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Polistes bahamensis''''' is a large [[species]] of colourful [[paper wasp]] in the genus ''[[Polistes]]'' of the family [[Vespidae]] which occurs in the [[Bahamas]], [[Florida]] and [[Louisiana]].<ref name=GBIF/><ref name=BugGuide>{{cite web |url=https://bugguide.net/node/view/87100 |title=Species ''Polistes bahamensis'' |last=Bentley |first=Tom |last2=Moisset |first2=Beatriz |date=2 February 2009 |website=BugGuide.Net |publisher=Department of Entomology, [[Iowa State University]] |access-date=17 January 2020}}</ref> It is also said to occur in [[Georgia (state)|Georgia]].<ref name=BugGuide/><ref name=narod>{{cite web |url=http://vespabellicosus2008.narod.ru/pdf6.pdf |title=Distributional Checklist of Species of the Genus ''Polistes'' (Hymenoptera: Vespidae; Polistinae, Polistini) }}</ref> \n\n==Taxonomy==\nIt was first described as an [[endemic]] new species from the Bahamas by [[Joseph Charles Bequaert]] and [[:species:George Salt|George Salt]] in 1931, consisting of three [[Variety_(botany)#Other_nomenclature_uses|varieties]] based on geography and patterns of coloured markings, ''P. bahamensis'' var. ''bahamensis'', ''P. bahamensis'' var. ''bilineolatus'' and ''P. bahamensis'' var. ''picturatus''. The [[Subspecies#Nominate subspecies|nominate]] variety of ''bahamensis'' was reported to be an [[endemic]] of [[Andros Island]], var. ''bilineolatus'' was only found in the central islands of [[New Providence Island|New Providence]] and [[Eleuthera]], and var. ''picturatus'' was known from [[Acklins]], [[Mariguana]], [[Rum Cay]], [[Crooked Island, Bahamas|Crooked Island]], [[Long Island, Bahamas|Long Island]], [[Watlings Island]] and [[Cat Island, Bahamas|Cat Island]].<ref name=Bequaert1931>{{cite journal |last=Bequaert |first=Joseph Charles |author-link=Joseph Charles Bequaert |last2=Salt |first2=George |author-link2=species:George Salt |date=1 December 1931 |title=New West Indian Diploptera |url=https://digitalcommons.usu.edu/bee_lab_ba/281/ |journal=Annals of the Entomological Society of America |volume=24 |issue=4 |pages=765\u2014797 |doi=10.1093/aesa/24.4.765 |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Bequaert1940>{{cite journal |last=Bequaert |first=Joseph Charles |author-link=Joseph Charles Bequaert |date=1940 |title=An Introductory Study of ''Polistes'' in the United States and Canada with Descriptions of Some New North and South American Forms (Hymenoptera; Vespid\u00e6) |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/50711500 |journal=Journal of the New York Entomological Society |volume=48 |pages=14 |doi= |access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Snelling1955>{{cite journal |last=Snelling |first=Roy R. |author-link=Roy Snelling |date=14 January 1955 |title=Notes on some ''Polistes'' in the American Museum of Natural History, with descriptions of new North American subspecies (Hymenoptera, Vespidae) |url=http://digitallibrary.amnh.org/bitstream/handle/2246/4730//v2/dspace/ingest/pdfSource/nov/N1701.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |journal=American Museum Novitates |volume=1701 |pages=4\u20148 |doi= |access-date=25 January 2020}}</ref> In 1940 Bequaert subsumed the species and its three varieties under [[Polistes exclamans|''P. exclamans'']], as well as described another new variety in that species, ''P. exclamans'' var. ''louisianus'', from three female specimens caught in [[New Orleans]].<ref name=Bequaert1940/><ref name=Snelling1955/> \n\nIn 1955 the variety ''louisianus'' was [[synonym (taxonomy)|synonymised]] with ''P. exclamans'' ''[[sensu stricto]]'' by [[Roy Snelling]], who stated that after examining large amounts of the wasps from two nests recovered in New Orleans, the vast majority of the individual wasps were typical nominate forms of ''exclamans'', with only one or two individuals per nest displaying the colour patterns (reduced yellow markings) reported by Bequaert in 1940, and he furthermore states that he collected a single ''louisianus'' wasp in a very large colony of ''P. exclamans'' var. ''exclamans'' in [[Kansas]]. Snelling also expanded the distribution of the taxon outside of the Bahamas by reporting on the presence of ''P. exclamans'' var. ''bahamensis'' in southern Florida, stating some, but not all, of the 21 wasps collected in the Royal Palm State Park, a wooded grove which has now become the nucleus of [[the Everglades]], and the nearby [[Archbold Biological Station]] were somewhat different in colouration with ''bahamensis'', but that the collection of specimens as a whole integrated seamlessly with the colour pattern of insular specimens. Snelling continued to recognise the ''P. exclamans'' varieties ''bilineolatus'' and ''picturatus'' as Bahamanian endemics.<ref name=Snelling1955/> \n\nBequaert and Salt's three or four varieties were then treated as [[subspecies]] of ''P. exclamans'' by [[Owain Richards]] in 1978.<!--need verification in primary source--> \n\n[[Karl Vorse Krombein]] was apparently the first to associate the variety ''louisianus'' with ''P. exclamans'' var. ''bahamensis'' in 1979, attributing the synonymy to Snelling.<ref name=Krombein1979>{{cite book |last=Krombein |first=Karl Vorse |author-link=Karl Vorse Krombein |chapter=Vespoidea |chapter-url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4575572 |editor1-last=Krombein |editor1-first=Karl V. |editor2-last=Hurd |editor2-first=Paul D. Jr. |editor3-last=Smith |editor3-first=David R. |editor4-last=Burks |editor4-first=B. D. |date=1979 |title=Catalog of Hymenoptera in America North of Mexico |volume=2 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/4575673 |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press |page=1510\u20141515 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.5074}}</ref> In 1983 Snelling chose to re-recognise ''P. bahamensis'' as a valid species again, and while doing so synonymised the subspecies ''bilineolatus'' and ''picturatus'' and \"reiterated\" his conclusion regarding the variety ''louisianus'' -although by 1983 he was stating that he had synonymised it with ''bahamensis'' in 1955 instead of ''P. exclamans'' var. ''exclamans''. By recognising the New Orleans specimens as ''bahamensis'' in 1983, Snelling effectively expanded the known distribution of this taxon hundreds of kilometres down the coast of the [[Gulf of Mexico]].<ref name=Snelling1983/> As of 2017 Kons and Rowan consider that all or at least part of the US population should be split off into a separate species, ''P. louisianus''; -these writers believe that many ''Polistes'' species should be split into numerous [[sympatric]] species based on small differences in their body colour.<ref name=Kons2017b/><ref name=Kons2017>{{cite web |url=http://www.lepidopterabiodiversity.com/Vespidae/CL/bahamensis.htm |title=''Polistes bahamensis'' specimen images in A Preliminary Illustrated Check List of the Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |last=Kons |first=Hugo L. Jr. |last2=Rowan |first2=Rex |date=2017 |website=The Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |publisher=Lepidoptera Biodiversity LLC |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Etymology===\nThe [[etymology]] of the [[specific epithet]] ''bahamensis'' is from the place 'the Bahamas', combined with the [[Latin language|Latin]] [[suffix]] [[:wikt:-ensis#Suffix|''-ensis'']], meaning 'of, or from, (a place)' or 'pertaining to', together forming an adjective with the meaning: 'of the Bahamas'.\n\n==Description==\nThe identification of this species has always been very difficult. When Bequaert first examined the first three specimens from New Orleans around 1940, he at first thought them to be perhaps [[Polistes crinitus|''P. crinitus'']] or [[Polistes versicolor|''P. versicolor'']] introduced from the [[Caribbean]].<ref name=Bequaert1940/> Snelling examined the same population and classified it as ''P. exclamans'' var. ''exclamans'' in 1955.<ref name=Snelling1955/>\n\nIt has also been seen as very similar to [[Polistes annularis|''P. annularis'']], with which it shares a slender first [[metasoma]]l segment. It can be distinguished from this species by the yellow spot on the [[mesopleuron]], and almost always having a yellow apical band on the posterior (back) margin of the [[tergum|tergites]] and more developed yellow markings on the mesosoma.<ref name=BugGuide/>\n\n==Distribution==\nThe known range has expanded as certain populations of wasps were determined to be this species, and with the collection of more specimens. \n\n===Bahamas===\nThe first specimens were first collected on [[New Providence Island]] in 1909. Bequaert and Salt described the species in 1931 from specimens collected on [[Acklins]], [[Andros Island]], [[Cat Island, Bahamas|Cat Island]], [[Crooked Island, Bahamas|Crooked Island]], [[Eleuthera]], [[Long Island, Bahamas|Long Island]], [[Mariguana]], New Providence Island, [[Rum Cay]] and [[Watlings Island]].<ref name=Bequaert1931/><ref name=Bequaert1940/><ref name=Snelling1955/> Specimens were first collected on [[Mayaguana]] in 1996, and the reported range was extended further to [[Great Inagua]] in 2011, with the species now believed to occur on all the major islands of the Bahamas,<ref name=Starr2011>{{cite journal |last=Starr |first=Christopher K. |last2=Sewlal |first2=Jo-Anne N. |date=2011 |title=A Range Extension of the Social Wasp ''Polistes bahamansis'' (Hymenoptera: Vespidae) |url=https://uwispace.sta.uwi.edu/dspace/bitstream/handle/2139/13082/2011-P.BAHAMENSIS.pdf;sequence=1 |journal=International Journal of Bahamian Studies |volume=17 |issue=2 |pages=1\u20142 |doi= |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===USA===\nSnelling first extended the range of this species to southern [[Florida]] when he identified a group of specimens of wasps collected there since the late 1930s as belonging to this species in a 1955 article. The ''louisianus'' colour form described by Bequaert in 1940, considered a synonym of the nominate taxon of ''P. exclamans'' by Snelling at the time, was initially only known from [[New Orleans]], but Snelling also described having seen a single individual in a nest of ''P. exclamans'' in [[Kansas]].<ref name=Snelling1955/> The taxon is included in the 1979 ''Catalog of Hymenoptera in America north of Mexico'', which for some reason does not include endemic varieties found in the Bahamas as found in America north of Mexico, as a subspecies of ''P. exclamans''. In this work ''louisianus'' is considered a synonym of ''P. exclamans'' var. ''bahamensis'', and the distribution is given as from \"Louisiana to Florida\".<ref name=Krombein1979/>\n\nSnelling reported the presence of this taxon in the USA again in 1983, stating its range included Florida, [[Georgia (state)|Georgia]] and [[Louisiana]].<ref name=BugGuide/><ref name=Kons2017/> A photograph of a number of wasps building a nest in coastal [[North Carolina]] in 2017 has been identified as being of this species.<ref name=GBIF/>\n\n==Ecology==\nIt has usually been recorded nesting under [[eaves]] of roofs of buildings<ref name=Starr2011/><ref name=Kons2018nests>{{cite web |url=http://www.lepidopterabiodiversity.com/Vespidae/AppendixB.htm |title=APPENDIX B: Nest Mate Associations of Florida Polistinae Species |last=Kons |first=Hugo L. Jr. |last2=Rowan |first2=Rex |date=2018 |website=The Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |publisher=Lepidoptera Biodiversity LLC |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> and sometimes under palm fronds.<ref name=BugGuide/><ref name=Starr2011/> The nest is suspended from an attachment stalk known as a [[Petiole_(insect_anatomy)#Other uses|petiole]].<ref name=Starr2011/>\n\nAs of 2017, no [[Strepsiptera]]n parasites are reported for ''P. bahamensis''.<ref name=Kons2018Strepsi>{{cite web |url=http://www.lepidopterabiodiversity.com/Vespidae/AppendixI.htm |title=APPENDIX I: Stylopized Florida Polistinae |last=Kons |first=Hugo L. Jr. |last2=Rowan |first2=Rex |date=2018 |website=The Paper Wasps and Hornets of Florida (Hymenoptera: Vespidae: Polistinae & Vespinae) |publisher=Lepidoptera Biodiversity LLC |access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Conservation==\nIt is quite common in the centre of its range, such as on New Providence Island, especially in urban areas such as the capital city [[Nassau, Bahamas|Nassau]]. In common with most species, the abundance diminishes at the edges of its distribution, being quite rare on Great Inagua and Mayaguana and \"sporadic\" along the Gulf Coast of Florida.<ref name=Starr2011/>\n\nThe [[IUCN]] has [[not evaluated]] this species' [[Conservation_status#IUCN_Red_List_of_Threatened_Species|conservation status]].<ref name=GBIF/>\n\nIt has been recorded as present in the following [[protected areas]]:\n*[[Archbold Biological Station]], [[Lake Placid, Florida|Lake Placid]], [[Highlands County, Florida|Highlands County]], Florida, USA.<ref name=Snelling1955/>\n*[[Emeralda Marsh Conservation Area]], [[Lake County, Florida|Lake County]], Florida, USA.<ref name=BugGuide/>\n*[[Inagua National Park]], Great Inagua, the Bahamas.<ref name=Starr2011/>\n*[[Everglades National Park]], Florida, USA.<ref name=Snelling1955/>\n*[[Watermelon Pond Wildlife Management Area]], [[Alachua County, Florida|Alachua County]], Florida, USA.<ref name=Kons2018nests/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q14422670}}\n\n[[Category:Polistes|bahamensis]]\n[[Category:Insects described in 1931]]\n\n\n{{Vespidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGeorgia(link changed toGeorgia (U.S. state); link changed toGeorgia (U.S. state)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polistes_bahamensis"}
{"title_page": "Michael McConnell and Jack Baker", "text_new": "{{other people||Jack Baker (disambiguation)}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=odd colors and fonts need to be removed, citations need to be standardized, spurious bold removed, citations checked (too many are primay), general layout and organization: article is laid out as a timeline--of what? the lead doesn't even clarify what the subject is, and the first sentence doesn't comply with MOS|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:MikeMcConnellJackBaker.jpg|thumb|Husbands Mike McConnell (left) and Jack Baker in 2016]]\n'''Michael McConnell''', [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s | librarian]], and '''Jack Baker''', [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s | law student]], were married<ref name=\"Marriage law\"> 1970: \"Minnesota Statutes Annotated\", ''West Publishing&nbsp;Co.''\n* Chapter&nbsp;517.01: '''Marriage a civil contract'''. \"Marriage, so far as its validity in law is concerned, is a civil contract, to which the consent of the parties, capable in law of contracting, is essential.\" \n* Chapter&nbsp;517.03: '''Marriages prohibited'''. [The list does not include parties of the same gender.]</ref> in the U.S. state of [[Minnesota]] on 3&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971.\n\nBoth were activists in Minnesota from 1969 to 1980. They were invited often to appear publicly in the US and Canada at college events, schools, businesses, churches, etc.<ref>See: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;2c and 2d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> \n\nHistorians insisted that they became the \"first same-sex couple in history to be legally married\".<ref name=Kraemer /> Specifically, the decision of [[Baker_v._Nelson#Facts_and_trial | Minnesota's Supreme Court]] in 1971 [[Baker_v._Nelson | did \"not reach back]] to Baker and McConnell\" since the two obtained their license and were married \"a full six weeks\"<ref name=FLR /> previously. The National Archives came to the same conclusion.<ref name=Archives>Anon., \"Hidden Treasures from the Stacks: pushing for equality\", ''The&nbsp;National Archives at Kansas City'', September&nbsp;2013, 7; [https://www.archives.gov/kansas-city/press/newsletter/2013-september.pdf#page=7 available online]</ref>\n\n==Student activism==\n\nWeeks before the 1969 [[Stonewall riots]], two activists and local friends organize a team called \"Fight Repression of Erotic Expression\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mnhs.org/cms/display?irn=10262356|title=Twin Cities Gay and Lesbian Community Oral History Project: Interview with Koreen Phelps : Collections Online : mnhs.org|website=collections.mnhs.org|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> as part of an outreach program sponsored by MINNESOTA FREE UNIVERSITY.<ref>Program offices were located in the Cedar Riverside Neighborhood of '''Minneapolis''', at 529&nbsp;Cedar&nbsp;Avenue, near the U of Minnesota's expanding campus on the West&nbsp;Bank of the Mississippi.\n* See: K.A.&nbsp;Phelps, \"The Homosexual Revolution\", ''MINNESOTA FREE UNIVERSITY'', 18&nbsp;'''May'''&nbsp;1969; Bulletin&nbsp;No.&nbsp;5, New Courses [final entry].\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''May''': Robert Halfhill, a graduate student with interest in their proposal, leaves the neighborhood lectures to form an independent group called \"FREE\" on the [[University of Minnesota|Minneapolis campus]] of the University of Minnesota.<ref name=Halfhill>Bruce Johasen, \"Out of Silence\", Minnesota History, Spring&nbsp;2019:\n* \"Halfhill steered the group through the administrative channels needed to establish FREE as a student group, 189. Lack of interest by women \"was always a bitter disappointment\" for Phelps, 188, who was \"really angry\" with demands for \"the right to get married\", 194;\n* Also: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''. On page 1:\n* \"Timidity and confusion\" tired Halfhill. \"He left to organize an independent coalition of activists on the East Bank campus.\"</ref> Those attending his meetings elect [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|Jack Baker, a law student]],<ref>Jack Baker, while a law student, was \n* president of FREE (1969), and\n* later, a student body president on \n* the Minneapolis campuses of \n* the University of Minnesota, \n* [elected 1971, re-elected 1972]</ref> to serve as president.<ref>Neal R. Peirce, \"The Great Plains States of America: People, Politics, and Power in the Nine Great Plains States\", ''George&nbsp;J. McLeod'' (1973), 145; [https://books.google.com/books?id=JyqbTl9fsc4C&pg=PA145& available online], accessed February 7, 2014</ref> \n\n* '''November''': A faculty committee qualifies FREE for all privileges enjoyed by student organizations.<ref name=dynes>Wayne R. Dynes, \"Homosexuality and Government, Politics and Prisons\" (1992), 248; [https://books.google.com/books?id=wegoALly5DEC&pg=PA244& available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref> As the \"the first student gay organization to gain recognition in the upper mid-west,\"<ref name= FREE>\"Minnesota Hosts First Legally Sanctioned Same-Sex Marriage\"\n* '''For Release''', ''Minnesota Student Association'', 7&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971.\n* also, '''for immediate release''', ''FREE'', 17&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970.\n* and, '''News from''', ''Fight Repression of Erotic Expression'', 1&nbsp;November&nbsp;1969\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> interest in FREE expands quickly. Its \"leaders believe it to be the first such organization on a Big Ten campus\", the second such organization in the United States, following the [[Student Homophile League]]<ref>Merged later with the [[Columbia Queer Alliance]].</ref> recognized by [[Columbia University]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schumach|first=Murray|title=Columbia Charters Homosexual Group|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/05/03/107188654.pdf|accessdate=July 23, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 3, 1967}}</ref>\n\n'''1970''': Moving openly and aggressively, FREE slowly transforms [[Minneapolis]].<ref name=Coverage>On page&nbsp;13: \"A mecca for gays\", in a story by\n* Lily Hansen, ''GAY'', \"F.R.E.E. At Last\", 11&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970.  \n* also, \"Three big companies say they hire Gays\", ''The&nbsp;Advocate'', 30&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970.\n* and, Ken Bronson, \"A Quest for Full Equality\", 2004; [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf#page=9 available online] from ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* One member asks five major companies to explain their attitudes toward gay men and women.<ref name=Coverage /> Three large companies respond quickly, insisting that they did not discriminate against homosexuals in their hiring policies.<ref name=Coverage /> [[Honeywell]] objects:<ref name=Honeywell>An inquiry about employment of homosexuals generates a response from Gerry&nbsp;E. Morse, Vice President, ''Honeywell&nbsp;Inc.''. \n* See: letter to '''FREE''', addressed to James&nbsp;W. Chesebro, 29&nbsp;June&nbsp;1970.\n* and: Lars Bjornson, \"A quiet win: Honeywell yields\", ''The Advocate'', 10&nbsp;April&nbsp;1974, 13.\n* Courtesy: Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \"We would not employ a known homosexual.\" That member expands his surveys as complaints surface.\n\n* Another member is eager to educate his parents. For credit, he selects a program requested by Dave Moore, then a popular announcer on WCCO-TV. The student is proud of what ultimately airs on Sunday, 30&nbsp;September 1973.<ref>Review the FREE member's course work, including words to his parents.\n* Courtesy: \"Human Relations\", ''University Media Resources''\n* {{YouTube|id=mOwGW-Jie7E&feature=c4-overview&list=UU0ClfyXL_loos5QtXwPhMhQ|title=available online}}\n* Posted by Brandon Wolf </ref> \n\n* Members vote to endorse<ref name=FREE /> [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|\"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\"]].<ref name=memoir>Memoir of Michael McConnell, as told to Gail Langer Karwoski, \"The Wedding Heard 'Round the World: America's First Gay Marriage,\" ''University of Minnesota Press'', 2016</ref><ref name=Halfhill />\n\n'''1972''': FREE continues working with a faculty committee to craft a new policy that would protect gay students from discrimination.<ref name=policy>See: letter to Jack Baker et al., from\n* Malcolm Moos, President, ''University of Minnesota'', 11&nbsp;February&nbsp;1971.  \"I appreciate your willingness to serve on the Campus Committee on Placement Services\";\n* also: Gary Urban, \"Complaint charges Honeywell discrimination\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 12&nbsp;March&nbsp;1973, 8; \n* Courtesy: Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''May''': Central Administration approves a final draft.<ref name=policy /> \n\n* Campus Committee on Placement Services accepts complaints of unequal treatment by employers recruiting on campus. \n\n'''1974''': When faced with a denial of access to students, Honeywell \"quietly reverses its hiring policy\".<ref name=Honeywell /> No longer would it refuse to employ students who were openly gay.\n\n===Gay Pride===\n'''1971''': After the Stonewall Rebellion \u2013 New York City, 1969<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/04/us/stonewall-riots-gay-pride.html|title=50 Years Later, What We Forgot About Stonewall|last=Salam|first=Maya|date=2019-06-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/ston/index.htm|title=Stonewall National Monument (U.S. National Park Service)|last=York|first=Mailing Address: 26 Wall Street Federal Hall National Monument c/o Stonewall National Monument New|last2=Us|first2=NY 10005 Phone: 212-668-2577 Contact|website=www.nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> \u2013 members of FREE from ''Gay&nbsp;House'' promote self-pride with picnics in Loring Park, near Downtown Minneapolis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mnhs.org/cms/display?irn=10262356|title=Twin Cities Gay and Lesbian Community Oral History Project: Interview with Koreen Phelps : Collections Online : mnhs.org|website=collections.mnhs.org|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> Thom Higgins<ref name=Pride>A monk turned gay activist.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> crafts \"Gay Pride\" as a chant to discredit the two terms often condemned as \"sins\" by the Catholic archbishop for Minneapolis and Saint Paul. \n\n'''2018''': \"The wrenching bankruptcy that forced a reckoning on the Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis for decades of clergy sexual abuse has culminated in a $230 million settlement for roughly 450 victims, the largest of its kind nationwide.\"<ref>Victims' attorney Jeff Anderson is overcome with emotion.\n* Staff writers, \"$210 in Atonement\", ''Star&nbsp;Tribune'', 1&nbsp;June&nbsp;2018,&nbsp;A1\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\n===Student Body President===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Shoes poster 1971.tif|thumb|right|1971 election poster]]  -->\n'''1971''': Baker campaigned to become president of the Minnesota Student Association<ref name=\"Student Body President\">A student body president known by different names; elected 1971, re-elected 1972. \n* March&nbsp;1942: Richard John Baker, Certificate of Birth \n* September&nbsp;1969: Jack Baker, name adopted to lead activists demanding gay equality \n* August&nbsp;1971: Pat&nbsp;Lyn McConnell, married name; by Decree of Adoption \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''\n* also, Kay Tobin and Randy Wicker, \"The&nbsp;Gay Crusaders\", ''Paperback Library'', New&nbsp;York:&nbsp;1972, 136</ref> on the U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M's Minneapolis campus. \"''Student Control over Student Concerns''\",<ref name=Platform>Platform for student body president \n* Jack Baker, \"Policy Statement\", March&nbsp;1971\n* Endorsed by ''Minnesota Daily'', \"Baker for MSA president\", 5&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;page&nbsp;4. \"He has spoken truth to power because he knows the power of truth.\"\n* After graduation, the Governor signed into law a bill reserving one seat on the Board of Regents for an enrolled student.</ref> urged students \"to search out a new self-respect.\"<ref name=\"Student Body President\" /> Thoughtful posters with a focus on [https://box8661.blogspot.com/2013/06/marriage-equality-was-inevitable.htm self-pride] helped his election,<ref name=election>A total of 6,024 ballots cast topped the previous record of 5,049 in the 1958 election.\n* See: Steve Brandt, \"Baker wins in record vote,\" ''Minnesota Daily'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;1\n* and, Gary Dawson, \"Homosexual Credits U Election Victory to a New Sophistication\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Dispatch'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;35\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> and re-election. <ref name=re-election>It was \"the first time in the 121-year history of the U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M that a student body president has been re-elected.\"\n* See: Vic Stoner, \"Baker, Schwartz win MSA election\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 7&nbsp;April&nbsp;1972,&nbsp;1\n* and, Associated Press, \"Law senior elected U. student president\", ''Austin Daily Herald'', 7&nbsp;April&nbsp;1972,&nbsp;p.&nbsp;?\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref>\n\n* \"We need a student on the Board of Regents,\" he insisted. No need to wait for a new law.<ref name=Platform /> \"The Regents already have the power to appoint students to all committees of the Board or Regents.\" \n\n* Baker captured 2,766&nbsp;votes;<ref name=election /> two competitors and write-in candidates split the remainder. \n\n* As student body president, Baker continued to question why the Board of Regents ignored students when making its decisions. Soon, one non-voting student was invited to sit with the regents at each committee meeting.<ref name=Platform /> \n\n'''1972''': Re-elected with \"3,035 votes out of a record turnout of 7,441\"<ref name=re-election /> \u2013 41% in a 3-way race.\n\n== Same-sex marriage activism ==\n\n===Lawsuit to obtain a licence===\n{{Main|Baker v. Nelson}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:McConnell (l) and Baker (r) apply for marriage license 19700518.png|thumb|right|Michael McConnell (l) and Jack Baker (18&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970) - by R. Bertrand Heine, Minnesota&nbsp;Historical&nbsp;Society]]  -->\n\n'''1970''': Minnesota's statutes do not explicitly forbid marriage between two adult men.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> Baker, a law student, argues that \"[[Everything which is not forbidden is allowed|what is not forbidden is permitted]]\"<ref>Jack Baker, as told to Helen Barrett, \"We had America's first gay marriage - in 1971\", ''Financial Times Magazine'', 7&nbsp;August&nbsp;2015; [https://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9d35d5d8-3ae4-11e5-bbd1-b37bc06f590c.html available online]</ref> when the couple applies for a marriage license in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> The Clerk of District Court<ref>18 May: Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; [[Hennepin County Government Center|Hennepin County]], Minnesota</ref>, Gerald Nelson, denies their request. Refusal by the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Facts_and_trial|lower courts]] to order Nelson to issue a license<ref>All claims were dismissed.\n* See: Associated Press, \"Marriage Is Out\", ''Kansas&nbsp;City Star'', 24&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;30A\n* and, \"Gay Marriage Plea Is Denied\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer Press'', 19&nbsp;November&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;27\n* and, \"Court Won't Let Men Wed\", ''N.Y.&nbsp;Times'', 10&nbsp;Jan.&nbsp;1971, 65\n* also, Appellant's Jurisdictional Statement, ''[[Baker_v._Nelson]]'', Minnesota Supreme Court docket no.&nbsp;71-1027, at 3&nbsp;-&nbsp;4 (statement of the case)</ref> is affirmed by the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|Minnesota Supreme Court]].<ref>\"The institution of marriage as a union of man and woman, uniquely involving the procreation or rearing of children within a family, is as old as the book of Genesis\".\n* \"Opinion\", by Justice C.&nbsp;Donald Peterson, ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'', 15&nbsp;Oct&nbsp;1971, 191&nbsp;N.W.2d&nbsp;185 at&nbsp;186.</ref>\n\n* Leadership inside the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] shows \"little or no enthusiasm\" for support.<ref>Letter from Norman Dorsen (General Counsel for ''ACLU'' in 1970),\n* published by Jason Smith, \"Gay Pride Block Party Case\", ''Friends of the Bill of Rights Foundation'', January&nbsp;2012,&nbsp;52 \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/pdf/rare/gayprideblockparty.pdf#page=54 available online]\n* Courtesy: ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Court rules in effect allow the '''''Minnesota Civil Liberties Union''''' to appeal Minnesota's \"opinion\" directly to the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref name=NYT051715>{{cite news |last=Eckholm |first=Eric|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|accessdate=May 17, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2015}}</ref>  \n\n* Allan Spear, a U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M professor of history, describes them as the \"lunatic fringe\".<ref>David von Drehle, \"Gay Marriage Already Won\", ''TIME'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;2013,&nbsp;22</ref>  \n\n* The case receives extensive media attention,<ref name=letters+>See, a matrix of items (late 1960s, 1970s, early 1980),\n* especially, Jack Star, \"The Homosexual Couple,\" ''LOOK'', 26&nbsp;January&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;69&nbsp;-&nbsp;71\n* and, Michael Durham, \"Homosexuals in revolt\", ''LIFE'', 31&nbsp;December&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;68\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Gift&nbsp;#6, the marriage that made history\", Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> including appearances on the ''[[Phil Donahue Show]]'',<ref name=comdon>{{cite news |last=Condon |first=Patrick|title=Minn. gay couple in '71 marriage case still joined|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2012/12/10/news/jack-baker-michael-mcconnell-same-sex-marriage|accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=Minnesota Public Radio|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> and Kennedy&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Co. (WLS-TV, Chicago&nbsp;IL). On the ''[[David Susskind Show]]''<ref>[http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2013/05/15/old-video Available online] from Sasha Aslanian, \"Gay rights pioneers Jack Baker and Michael McConnell predicted marriage victory in '70s\", ''Minnesota Public Radio'' (16&nbsp;May&nbsp;2013)</ref> (New&nbsp;York,&nbsp;NY), Baker is blunt.<ref name=Bowes /> \"We're gonna win eventually, not this time but maybe the next time around.\" \n\n'''1972''': The clerk for Justice Harry Blackmun crafts a one-sentence rejection because \"I just [didn't] think the court was ready at the time to take on the issue.\"<ref>Jess Bravin, \"Supreme Court Clerk Remembers First Same-Sex Marriage Case\", ''The Wall Street Journal'', 1&nbsp;May&nbsp;2015; [https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-clerk-remembers-first-same-sex-marriage-case-1430494015 available online]</ref> A quick dismissal of ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'' is approved unanimously.<ref name=greenhouse /> \n\n'''2015''': The high court allows lower courts to supervise a national debate before deciding that its decision to dismiss demands for marriage equality must be overruled.<ref>\"The Court now holds that same-sex couples may exercise the fundamental right to marry.\"\n* ''Obergefell&nbsp;v. Hodges,'' 26&nbsp;June&nbsp;2015, at&nbsp;22-23 \n* [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/14pdf/14-556_3204.pdf#page=28 available online]</ref>\n\n* Gay Marriage is \"rejected by early gay activists [in New&nbsp;York City] who were mostly interested in sexual freedom and gay liberation.\"<ref>Thomas Kraemer, \"Jack Baker deserves mainstream press coverage after gay marriage ruling\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', 7&nbsp;July&nbsp;2012; [http://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2012/07/jack-baker-deserves-mainstream-press.html available online]</ref>\n\n* Gay \"historians\" ignore Minnesota because they \"personally had political objections to gay marriage activism.\"<ref>Minnesotans document gay history:\n* See: Thomas Kraemer [Professor], \"Gay marriage pioneer Jack Baker starts blog\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', 4&nbsp;April&nbsp;2012; [https://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2012/04/gay-marriage-pioneer-jack-baker-starts.html available online]\n* also, Jack Baker [Attorney], \"A court corrupted\"; [https://box8661.blogspot.com/2015/03/a-court-corrupted.html available online]</ref>\n\n===A civil right===\nIn 1970, [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|McConnell and Baker]] apply for a license to marry. The Clerk of District Court<ref>18 May: Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; Hennepin County, Minnesota</ref> rejects their request.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> McConnell re-applies in a different county and receives a marriage license.<ref>16&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971: Clerk of District Court, Fifth Judicial District, in Mankato \n* 3 September: At a ceremony in Minneapolis, Hennepin County, a United Methodist minister certifies the marriage contract.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder #7], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> Their wedding is proclaimed to be [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|\"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\"]].<ref name=memoir /> Assistant Chief Judge Gregory Anderson rules (2018) that \"The marriage is declared to be in all respects valid.\"<ref name=ruling>McConnells against Blue Earth County, \u201cCONCLUSIONS OF LAW\u201d, Fifth Judicial District, File&nbsp;#07-CV-16-4559, 18&nbsp;September&nbsp;2018. \n* \"The September&nbsp;3,&nbsp;1971 marriage of James&nbsp;Michael McConnell and Pat&nbsp;Lyn McConnell, a/k/a Richard&nbsp;John Baker, has never been dissolved or annulled by judicial decree and no grounds currently exist on which to invalidate the marriage.\" \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/McConnellvBlueEarthCounty-17-Sept-2018-ConclusionsofLaw_ORDER.pdf#page=4 Available online] from U of Minnesota Libraries.\n* Courtesy: McConnell&nbsp;Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder&nbsp;#4], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\nBaker is invited to address members of the Ramsey County Bar Association. Same-sex unions are \"not only authorized by the U.S. Constitution\"<ref>Bob Protzman, \"Gay Marriage OK Predicted\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer&nbsp;Press'', 22&nbsp;October&nbsp;1971, p&nbsp;?</ref> but are mandatory, he explains. \"I&nbsp;am convinced that same-sex marriages will be legalized in the United States.\"\n\n'''1972''': Baker speaks to a forum of more than 2,000 at the [[University of Winnipeg]]. \"We maintain that it's a matter of equity and fair play that if a state is going to give childless heterosexual couples rights and benefits under the law, they can't complain when childless same-sex couples ask for the same rights.\"<ref name=\"Canada\">Persistence spread first to Canada, than worldwide.\n* See: Jack Baker, \"The right to be human and gay\", ''Manitoban'', 13&nbsp;March&nbsp;1972,\n* as reprinted by Ken Bronson in \"A Quest for Full Equality\", 2004, 69,  \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf#page=73 available online] from ''University  of Minnesota Libraries'';\n* also, Mia Rabson, \"Couple helped make history\", ''Winnipeg Free&nbsp;Press'', 17&nbsp;September&nbsp;2004, A4 and \n* letter from Rich North to Jack [Baker] & Mike [McConnell], 20&nbsp;September&nbsp;2004); [http://box8661.blogspot.com/2012/04/letter-from-canada-2.html available online].\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> The lecture persuades Richard North to begin a \"fight to be married\" to Chris Vogel.<ref name=Canada /> His persistence leads to marriage equality in [[Canada]] during 2004.<ref name= Canada />\n\n'''2012''': Demands for same-sex marriage continue to grow worldwide, becoming \"the civil rights issue of our times\".<ref name=\"never in doubt\">Lecture by NAACP President Benjamin Todd Jealous, during a news conference at the organization's national headquarters.\n* Michael&nbsp;K. Lavers, \"NAACP president: Marriage is '''civil rights issue of our times'''\" ''Washington Blade'', 21&nbsp;May&nbsp;2012; [http://www.washingtonblade.com/2012/05/21/naacp-president-marriage-is-civil-rights-issue-of-our-times/ available online]\n* also, Patrick Condon, \"Gay couple in 1971 marriage ruling reflect on new court challenges\", ''Associated Press,'' as reprinted in the ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer&nbsp;Press'', 11&nbsp;December&nbsp;2012, 3A+.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;7a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> Speaking to the ''Associated Press'', Baker explained that the \"outcome was never in doubt because the conclusion was intuitively obvious to a first-year law student.\"<ref name=\"never in doubt\" /> Same-sex marriage is [[Baker_v._Nelson|legalized nationwide]] in 2015.\n\n=== Adoption, name change, marriage ===\nIn 1971, McConnell legally adopts<ref>FINDINGS AND DECREE [File No.&nbsp;AD-19962], 3&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971\n* Order signed by Judge Lindsay&nbsp;G. Arthur, Juvenile Division\n* Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; Hennepin County, Minnesota\n* See: Anon., \"U student head adopted by homosexual friend\", ''Minneapolis Tribune'', 25&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;1A\n* also, Associated Press, \"Male's adoption by roommate OKd\", ''Rocky Mountain News'', Denver, 26&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;85\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder&nbsp;#3, file&nbsp;#2], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Baker because \"regardless of popular conception, adoption is not limited to children\". Baker's legal name changes to Pat Lyn McConnell. They visit friends in [[Mankato]] where McConnell applies and receives a marriage license.<ref name=\"Free Press\">Issued by the Clerk of District Court, in [[Mankato]], Fifth Judicial District, [[Blue Earth County]] \n* See: \"Daily Record\", ''Mankato&nbsp;Free Press'', 16&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971, p.&nbsp;?\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder&nbsp;#7], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> The Rev. Roger Lynn, a [[United Methodist]] minister, validates their marriage contract.<ref name=Bowes>\"Pastor Roger Lynn holds up Baker and McConnell's marriage certificate\"\n* Claire Bowes, \"Jack Baker and Michael McConnell: Gay&nbsp;Americans who married in 1971\", ''BBC&nbsp;News Magazine'', 3&nbsp;July&nbsp;2013 \n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23159390 available online]. \n* A United Methodist minister officiated at a ceremony in Minneapolis, Hennepin County.</ref><ref name=FREE /> \n\n'''1972''': The Hennepin County Attorney convenes a grand jury, which \"studied the legality of the marriage but found the question not worth pursuing.\"<ref>\"Thus the marriage remained in effect.\"\n* See: \"Homosexual Wins Fight to Take Bar Examination in Minnesota\", ''New York Times'', 7&nbsp;January&nbsp;1973, 55. </ref>\n\n'''1974''': ''The&nbsp;Family Law Reporter''<ref name=FLR>Anon., \"Gay married couple frustrated in adoption bid\", ''The&nbsp;Family Law Reporter'', published by The&nbsp;Bureau of National Affairs, 10&nbsp;December&nbsp;1974, page&nbsp;2103</ref> argues that the \"federal constitution prohibition against ex post facto laws .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. forbids the imposition of punishment for past conduct lawful at the time it was engaged\".<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> Hence, the Minnesota high court's opinion \u2013 ''[[ Baker v. Nelson]]'' \u2013 does not reach back to Baker and McConnell because the two were married \"a full six weeks\" before that decision.\n\n'''2013''': Thomas Kraemer, a retired professor at [[Oregon State University]], concludes that &nbsp;FREE hosted \"the first same-sex couple in history to be legally married\".<ref name=Kraemer>Thomas Kraemer [professor, Oregon State University], \"Gay marriage discussion in 1953 vs.&nbsp;1963 and today\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', posted 16&nbsp;December&nbsp;2013; [http://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2013/12/gay-marriage-discussion-in-1953-vs-1963.html available online]</ref> Records at ''The National Archives''<ref name=Archives>Anon., \"Hidden Treasures from the Stacks: pushing for equality\", ''The&nbsp;National Archives at Kansas City'', September&nbsp;2013, 7; [https://www.archives.gov/kansas-city/press/newsletter/2013-september.pdf#page=7 available online]</ref> verify that \"McConnell and Baker's marriage license [from Blue&nbsp;Earth County, MN] was never revoked. They are still married and have been for the last forty two years.\"\n\n=== Federal courts respond ===\nValidity of the marriage depends on how Minnesota's [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|marriage law]] is interpreted.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> A direct appeal to the United States Supreme Court is [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|dismissed]].<ref>409 U.S. 810, 93&nbsp;S.Ct.&nbsp;37, 34&nbsp;L.Ed.2d&nbsp;65&nbsp;(1972)</ref> While an appeal to the Minnesota Supreme Court is pending, McConnell re-applies and obtains a [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#Adoption,_name_change,_marriage|marriage license]].<ref name=\"Free Press\" /> By ORDER of Assistant Chief Judge Gregory Anderson, \"The marriage is declared to be in all respects valid.\"<ref name=ruling />\n\n'''1971''': Both state and federal courts reject the marriage, others approve.<ref>\"What is believed to be the first same-sex marriage in the United States was performed in Minnesota.\"\n* Courtesy: Pat Kessler, \"A Rare Glimpse At Minn.'s 1st Gay Wedding In 1971\", ''WCCO'' [CBS, Minnesota], 31&nbsp;July&nbsp;2013; [http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/07/29/a-rare-glimpse-at-minns-1st-gay-wedding-in-1971/ available online].\n* also, Naomi Pescovitz, \"Pastor Reflects Back on Minn. Gay Marriage\", ''KSTP-TV'' [Minneapolis,&nbsp;MN], 16&nbsp;May&nbsp;2013; {{YouTube|5MdGM9xBIMQ|available online}}.\n* and, Associated Press, \"They're Mr. and Mr.\", ''San Francisco Chronicle'', 8&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;3</ref> \n\n'''1973''': A joint tax return for 1973 is rejected by the Internal Revenue Service.<ref>Anon., \"Homosexual Couple Contest I.R.S. Ban On a Joint Return\", ''The&nbsp;New York Times'', 5&nbsp;Jan.&nbsp;1975,&nbsp;55</ref>\n\n'''1974''': McConnell lists Baker as an [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#Adoption,_name_change,_marriage|adopted \"child\"]] on his tax returns from 1974 through 2004 for which he claims a deduction as [[head of household]]. That benefit ends when Congress limits the deduction for an adopted child under the age of 19.<ref>Anon., \"Form 1040 Instructions\", ''Internal Revenue Service'' (2005), 19; [https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-prior/i1040gi--2005.pdf#page=19 available online]</ref>\n\n'''1976''': A claim filed with the Veterans Administration is rejected<ref>''McConnell v. Nooner'':\n* District Court: No.&nbsp;4-75-Civ.&nbsp;566 (D.&nbsp;Minn. 20&nbsp;April&nbsp;1976)\n* and, United States Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit: 547&nbsp;F.2d&nbsp;54 (8th&nbsp;Cir.&nbsp;1976)</ref> because \"Minnesota law prohibits same sex marriages<ref>[[Baker_v._Nelson]], 291&nbsp;Minn.&nbsp;310, 191&nbsp;N.W.2d&nbsp;185&nbsp;(1971)</ref> .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.\"\n\n==Employment discrimination==\nThe University Librarian offers Michael McConnell the position of Head of the Cataloging Division at the library on the St.&nbsp;Paul campus.<ref name=\"job offer\"> '''1970''': Letter to Michael McConnell,\n* from Ralph&nbsp;H. Hopp, University Librarian, ''University of Minnesota'' [Minneapolis], 27&nbsp;April;\n* also, see Randy Tigue, \"Regent: FREE&nbsp;member case is a matter of public&nbsp;relations\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 16&nbsp;July,&nbsp;1;\n* and, letter from James&nbsp;F. Hogg, Secretary, Board of Regents, ''University of Minnesota'', 10&nbsp;July. \"... your conduct, as represented in the public and University news media, is not consistent with the best interest of the University.\" \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;5a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> After McConnell applies for a marriage license, regent&nbsp;Daniel Gainey insists that \"homosexuality is about the worst thing there is.\" \n\n'''1970''': The Board of Regents rejects the offer. McConnell sues in federal [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/316/809/1951718/ <span style=\"color:blue\">District Court</span>] and prevails.<ref>Bob Lundegaard, \"University Ordered to Hire Homosexual\", ''Minneapolis Tribune'', 10&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;23</ref>\n\n'''1971''': The Board appeals to the [https://openjurist.org/451/f2d/193/mcconnell-v-anderson <span style=\"color:blue\">Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals.</span>]<ref>Anon., \"Homosexual Wins a Suit over Hiring\", ''New York Times'', 20&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1970/09/20/355908502.pdf available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref> The panel concludes that the University did not restrict free speech. Instead, it was McConnell who wants \"to pursue an activist role in implementing his controversial ideas concerning the social status to be accorded homosexuals and thereby to foist tacit approval of the socially repugnant concept upon his employer.\"<ref>Michelle Andrea Wolf and Alfred P. Kielwasser, eds., \"Gay People, Sex, and the Media\", ''Haworth Press'' (1991), 237; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Y_Hd0F2J7LEC&pg=PA237& available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref>\n\n'''1972''': More than 80% of the student body voice disapproval of the regents' action.<ref>\"Do you think the University was justified in firing McConnell because of his open declaration of homosexuality?\"\n* yes&nbsp;=&nbsp;10%, no&nbsp;=&nbsp;81%, no opinion&nbsp;=&nbsp;8%, other&nbsp;=&nbsp;1%\n* See: Office of Student Affairs, \"Research Bulletin\", ''University of Minnesota'', Winter&nbsp;1972  \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;5a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> McConnell is hired by the [[Hennepin County Library]].<ref>1972: Then, a diverse and growing system of 26&nbsp;facilities; \n* he rises to the level of Coordinating Librarian before retiring.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes 6a-b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> When he retires 37&nbsp;years later, the Board of Commissioners commends him for his service.<ref>See: \"Item&nbsp;7A - Commendation of Michael McConnell\", ''Hennepin County Board of Commissioners'', 30&nbsp;November&nbsp;2010; [http://hennepinmn.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id=10&amp;clip_id=1134 available online].</ref>\n\n'''2012''': University president [[Eric Kaler]] offers McConnell an apology for the \"reprehensible\" treatment he endured from the Board of Regents in 1970.<ref>2012: \"News\", ''University News Service'', 22&nbsp;June\n* 2018: President Kaler affirmed his 2012 News statements. Action taken by our Board in 1970, he said, \"is today worthy of deep criticism - of rebuke and censure.\" See: Email to Logan Chelmo, 27&nbsp;June&nbsp;2018; class of 2018, Shakopee High School, located in Shakopee, Minnesota\n* 2020: McConnell is enrolled as a member of the Heritage Society of the President's Club. See: Letter from xxx, 6&nbsp;June&nbsp;2020  \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> McConnell accepts his assurance that \"such practices would not be consistent with the practices enforced today at the university.\"<ref>Gift&nbsp;#1 is accepted by Kristin Lockhart, Associate Vice President for Equity and Diversity, 25&nbsp;July.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder&nbsp;#8], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref>\n\n==Career in law and politics==\nIn June 1972, Baker led the DFL Gay Rights Caucus<ref>'''For Release Any Time''', \"Gay Machine Startles DFL Regulars\", ''DFL Gay Rights Caucus'', 9&nbsp;June&nbsp;1972.</ref> at the State Convention of the [[Minnesota Democratic\u2013Farmer\u2013Labor Party]]. When the caucus proposed \"legislation defining marriage as a civil contract between any two adults\",<ref>Resolution&nbsp;71.d, \"The 1972 DFL Platform\", ''Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor State Central Committee'', 9&nbsp;-&nbsp;11&nbsp;June&nbsp;1972 at Rochester, MN.</ref> the delegates approved that wording for inclusion in the party platform. This was the first time a major United States political party encouraged support for marriage equality.\n\nAfter he graduated from the [[University of Minnesota Law School]] in December,<ref>Malcolm Moos, President, ''University of Minnesota'', 13&nbsp;December&nbsp;1972: \"The Degree Of Juris Doctor With All Its Privileges And Obligations\" is conferred</ref> his request to take the bar examination raised questions of fraud surrounding his [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|1971 marriage license]]. At a hearing, Baker was defended by the Minnesota Civil Liberties Union.<ref>Anon., \"Marriage hurdle cleared, Baker to take bar exams\", ''Minneapolis Star'', 28&nbsp;December 1972,&nbsp;2</ref> He was admitted to the bar<ref> October 2002: In a MEMO for the record, Baker explains why lobbying by the Chief Justice, Oscar Knutson, failed to deny him a license to practice law.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;7a, section&nbsp;II], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> after the State Board of Law Examiners reviewed the facts and concluded that he was entitled to take the exam.<ref name=bar>{{cite news|title=Homosexual Wins Fights to Take Bar Examination in Minnesota|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/01/07/119453382.pdf |accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 7, 1973}}</ref> \n\nBaker campaigned for Associate Justice of the Minnesota Supreme Court five times. He argued that each opponent violated the Code of Judicial Conduct<ref name=\"Results\">Jack Baker questioned why some judges were allowed to ignore the Code of Judicial Conduct.\n* 1970: Canon&nbsp;5E. '''Arbitration'''. \"A judge should not act as an arbitrator or mediator.\" \n* 1994: Canon&nbsp;4F. '''Service as Arbitrator or Mediator'''. \"A judge shall not act as an arbitrator or mediator or otherwise perform judicial functions in a private capacity unless expressly authorized by law.\"\n* 1978: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=72 C. Donald Peterson]\n* 1980: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=73 George M. Scott]\n* 1982: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=74 John E. Simonett]\n* 1984: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=74 Douglas K. Amdahl]\n* 2002: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=84 Paul H. Anderson]\n* others\n* Courtesy: Douglas A. Hedrin, \"Results of Elections of Justices to the Minnesota Supreme Court 1857-2016\", ''Minnesota Legal History Project''\n* Details: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> by heading the [[C._Donald_Peterson#Minnesota News Council|Minnesota News Council]] (MNC). \n\nEthics of C. Donald Peterson were questioned in 1978, George Scott in 1980, John Simonett<ref>See: Initial Annual Registration for a Minnesota Non-Profit Corporation, ''Office of the Secretary of State''. \n* \"Effective August 1, 1989, all non-profit corporations are now required to file an annual registration once every calendar year. Please review the information on the label and read all directions before completing this form.\"\n* Corporate Charter Number: L-559 \n* Corporate Name: Minnesota News Council \n* [[Registered Office]] Address: '''230&nbsp;State&nbsp;Capital''', St.&nbsp;Paul, MN [chambers of the Minnesota Supreme Court before moving to a new location] \n* Signature: [Associate Justice] '''John&nbsp;E. Simonett''' \n* Title of Office: Chair \n* Date: 1/22/90\n* Courtesy: ''Minnesota Historical Society''</ref> in 1982, Douglas Amdahl in 1984 and [[Paul H. Anderson]] in 2002. In the ''Plebiscite'' mailed to more than 14,900 attorneys in Minnesota, Baker challenged the bar to end special relationships between Justices of Minnesota's Supreme Court and MNC.<ref name=\"rule_of_law\">Jack Baker, \"2002 Judicial '''Plebiscite'''\", ''Minnesota State Bar Association'', September&nbsp;2002\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Nevertheless, collusion continued.<ref>The list of \"Supreme Court Justices who chaired the News Council\"\n* 1971-80: C. Donald Peterson\n* [also: George M. Scott]\n* 1980-82: Douglas K. Amdahl\n* 1982-94: John E. Simonett\n* 1995-97: Paul H. Anderson\n* 1998-2006: Edward Stringer\n* See: email from Susan Hansen, <newscncl@mtn.org>, 14 June 2000.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume 7a], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, University of Minnesota Libraries</ref> \n\nBenefits bestowed on a judge who ignored the Code of Judicial Conduct and who [[C._Donald_Peterson#Minnesota News Council|helped to mediate]] private disputes continued even after the MNC was ejected from court chambers in 1994.<ref>Remaining offices for the Minnesota Supreme Court moved from 230&nbsp;State&nbsp;Capitol in January\n* \u201cEmployees coped. They moved into the newly remodeled space floor-by-floor and coexisted with construction over a period of time from September through '''December''' [1994].\u201d\n* See: Roland C. Amundson, \u201cA Search for Place: The History of the Minnesota Judicial Center\u201d, ''Minnesota Court of Appeals'', 1995,&nbsp;67.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref><ref>Not until James H. Gilbert resigned as Associate Justice and was hired by MNC in 2007 as its \"Hearing Chair\" did MNC stop recruiting judges to mediate its disputes.\n* See: email from Sarah E. Bauer, Interim Director, Minnesota News Council, 11&nbsp;May&nbsp;2007;\n* new address: '''12&nbsp;South Sixth&nbsp;Street''', Suite&nbsp;927, Minneapolis, MN&nbsp;55402.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> MNC ceased to exist in 2011.<ref>Gail Rosenblum, \"News council's demise is bad news for all who value the truth\", ''Star&nbsp;Tribune'', 23&nbsp;February 2011, B1</ref>\n\n==Later years==\n[[File:BakerMcConnell.jpg|thumb|Baker and McConnell in 2016]]\nIn 2003, Baker and McConnell amended their individual tax returns for the year 2000, filing jointly as a couple. They offered proof of a valid marriage license issued in Blue Earth County. The IRS challenged the validity of the marriage license and argued that, even if the license were valid, the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] prohibited the IRS from recognizing it. When McConnell brought suit, the [[United States District Court for the District of Minnesota|U.S. District Court for Minnesota]] upheld the IRS ruling<ref>{{cite web|title=McConnell v. United States, January 3, 2005|url=http://www.lawprofessorblogs.com/taxprof/linkdocs/2005-1056-1.pdf|publisher=US District Court for Minnesota|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> and the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed,<ref>{{cite web|title=McConnell v. United States, July 17, 2006|url=http://docs.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca8/05-1781/051781u-2011-02-25.pdf?1301253248|publisher=8th Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> saying that McConnell could not re-litigate the question decided in ''[[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|Baker v. Nelson]]''.\n\nThe U.S. Supreme Court agreed in 2015, \"to decide the issue Jack Baker and Mike McConnell tried to bring before it in 1972: Do same-sex couples have a constitutional right to get married?\"<ref>Roger Parloff, \"12 key moments that led to the Supreme Court's same-sex marriage case\", ''fortune.com'' (posted 16&nbsp;January&nbsp;2015); [http://fortune.com/2015/01/18/same-sex-marriage-supreme-court/ available online]</ref> Though [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|that case was dismissed]] \"for want of a substantial federal question\",<ref name=greenhouse>{{cite news |last=Greenhouse |first=Linda |title=Wedding Bells|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/20/wedding-bells/|accessdate=March 21, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 20, 2013}}</ref> the couple obtained a [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#A_civil_right|legal marriage license]] before the appeal began. Minnesota's Attorney General argued, as a friend of the court: \"The procreation rationale [used by the Minnesota Supreme Court] does not support the prohibition of same-sex marriage\".<ref name=swanson>Lori Swanson, Attorney General, State of Minnesota; \"Brief of the State of Minnesota as AMICUS CURIAE in support of petitioners\", Obergefell v. Hodges; ''In The Supreme Court of the United States'', March&nbsp;2015, 18; [http://thecolu.mn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/MNSCOTUSbrief.pdf#page=30 available online]</ref>\n\nBaker and McConnell were still living as a married couple as late as May 2015.<ref name=NYT051715>{{cite news |last=Eckholm |first=Eric|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|accessdate=May 17, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:MikeMcConnell.jpg|thumb|right|upright|McConnell in 2016]]\n\n==Interview==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2015/07/16/baker-mcconnell|title=For Mpls. couple, gay marriage ruling is a victory 43 years in the making|author=Tom Crann|date=16 July 2015|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio News}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-06-25/meet-two-men-who-managed-get-first-known-same-sex-marriage-license-back-1970|title=Meet the two men who managed to get the first known same-sex marriage license - back in 1970|author=T.J. Raphael|date=25 June 2015|publisher=The Takeaway, Public Radio International}}\n\n==Short documentary==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cse4s3gmbPE|title=Baker v. Nelson: The Original Case for Gay Marriage|author=Joseph Kase and Jeremiah Smith|date=Feb 2014|publisher=YouTube}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/07/29/a-rare-glimpse-at-minns-1st-gay-wedding-in-1971/|title=A Rare Glimpse At Minn.'s 1st Gay Wedding In 1971|author=Pat Kessler|date=29 July 2013|publisher=WCCO-TV, Minneapolis}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|author= Erik Eckholm|date=16 May 2015|publisher=www.nytimes.com|newspaper=The New York Times}}\n* {{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3843579/influential-marriages/|title=The 25 Most Influential Marriages of All Time|author=Lisa Grunwald|date=12 May 2015|magazine=TIME}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.qlibrary.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Seeds_for_Gay_Marriage_Equality.pdf#page=2|title=Who defined the gay agenda?|author=Pat Lyn McConnell|date=Jan 2014|publisher=[[Quatrefoil Library]]}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23159390|title=Jack Baker and Michael McConnell: Gay Americans who married in 1971|author=Claire Bowes|date=4 July 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|work=BBC News}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.qlibrary.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Quatrefolio-2012-Pride.pdf#page=5|title=Minnesota Led the Two Coasts on Marriage Rights, and Should Do So Again: Jack Baker and Michael McConnell|author=Robert Frame|year=2012|publisher=Quatrefoil Library}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf|title=A Quest for Full Equality|author=Ken Bronson|year=2004|publisher=University of Minnesota Libraries}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.brumm.com/schools/gaylib/earlybrumm.html#baker|title=My Own Early Gay History|author=Dennis Brumm|year=1971|publisher=www.brumm.com}}\n* Memoir of Michael McConnell (2016) as told to Gail Langer Karwoski, [http://www.worldcat.org/title/wedding-heard-round-the-world-americas-first-gay-marriage/oclc/926312828&referer=brief_results \"The Wedding Heard Heard 'Round the World: America's First Gay Marriage.\"], Minneapolis, MN: ''University of Minnesota Press''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Jack}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||Jack Baker (disambiguation)}}\n{{Cleanup|reason=odd colors and fonts need to be removed, citations need to be standardized, spurious bold removed, citations checked (too many are primay), general layout and organization: article is laid out as a timeline--of what? the lead doesn't even clarify what the subject is, and the first sentence doesn't comply with MOS|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:MikeMcConnellJackBaker.jpg|thumb|Husbands Mike McConnell (left) and Jack Baker in 2016]]\n'''Michael McConnell''', [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s | librarian]], and '''Jack Baker''', [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s | law student]], were married<ref name=\"Marriage law\"> 1970: \"Minnesota Statutes Annotated\", ''West Publishing&nbsp;Co.''\n* Chapter&nbsp;517.01: '''Marriage a civil contract'''. \"Marriage, so far as its validity in law is concerned, is a civil contract, to which the consent of the parties, capable in law of contracting, is essential.\" \n* Chapter&nbsp;517.03: '''Marriages prohibited'''. [The list does not include parties of the same gender.]</ref> in the U.S. state of [[Minnesota]] on 3&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971.\n\nBoth were activists in Minnesota from 1969 to 1980. They were invited often to appear publicly in the US and Canada at college events, schools, businesses, churches, etc.<ref>See: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;2c and 2d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> \n\nHistorians insisted that they became the \"first same-sex couple in history to be legally married\".<ref name=Kraemer /> Specifically, the decision of [[Baker_v._Nelson#Facts_and_trial | Minnesota's Supreme Court]] in 1971 [[Baker_v._Nelson | did \"not reach back]] to Baker and McConnell\" since the two obtained their license and were married \"a full six weeks\"<ref name=FLR /> previously. The National Archives came to the same conclusion.<ref name=Archives>Anon., \"Hidden Treasures from the Stacks: pushing for equality\", ''The&nbsp;National Archives at Kansas City'', September&nbsp;2013, 7; [https://www.archives.gov/kansas-city/press/newsletter/2013-september.pdf#page=7 available online]</ref>\n\n==Student activism==\n\nWeeks before the 1969 [[Stonewall riots]], two activists and local friends organize a team called \"Fight Repression of Erotic Expression\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mnhs.org/cms/display?irn=10262356|title=Twin Cities Gay and Lesbian Community Oral History Project: Interview with Koreen Phelps : Collections Online : mnhs.org|website=collections.mnhs.org|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> as part of an outreach program sponsored by MINNESOTA FREE UNIVERSITY.<ref>Program offices were located in the Cedar Riverside Neighborhood of '''Minneapolis''', at 529&nbsp;Cedar&nbsp;Avenue, near the U of Minnesota's expanding campus on the West&nbsp;Bank of the Mississippi.\n* See: K.A.&nbsp;Phelps, \"The Homosexual Revolution\", ''MINNESOTA FREE UNIVERSITY'', 18&nbsp;'''May'''&nbsp;1969; Bulletin&nbsp;No.&nbsp;5, New Courses [final entry].\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''May''': Robert Halfhill, a graduate student with interest in their proposal, leaves the neighborhood lectures to form an independent group called \"FREE\" on the [[University of Minnesota|Minneapolis campus]] of the University of Minnesota.<ref name=Halfhill>Bruce Johasen, \"Out of Silence\", Minnesota History, Spring&nbsp;2019:\n* \"Halfhill steered the group through the administrative channels needed to establish FREE as a student group, 189. Lack of interest by women \"was always a bitter disappointment\" for Phelps, 188, who was \"really angry\" with demands for \"the right to get married\", 194;\n* Also: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''. On page 1:\n* \"Timidity and confusion\" tired Halfhill. \"He left to organize an independent coalition of activists on the East Bank campus.\"</ref> Those attending his meetings elect [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|Jack Baker, a law student]],<ref>Jack Baker, while a law student, was \n* president of FREE (1969), and\n* later, a student body president on \n* the Minneapolis campuses of \n* the University of Minnesota, \n* [elected 1971, re-elected 1972]</ref> to serve as president.<ref>Neal R. Peirce, \"The Great Plains States of America: People, Politics, and Power in the Nine Great Plains States\", ''George&nbsp;J. McLeod'' (1973), 145; [https://books.google.com/books?id=JyqbTl9fsc4C&pg=PA145& available online], accessed February 7, 2014</ref> \n\n* '''November''': A faculty committee qualifies FREE for all privileges enjoyed by student organizations.<ref name=dynes>Wayne R. Dynes, \"Homosexuality and Government, Politics and Prisons\" (1992), 248; [https://books.google.com/books?id=wegoALly5DEC&pg=PA244& available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref> As the \"the first student gay organization to gain recognition in the upper mid-west,\"<ref name= FREE>\"Minnesota Hosts First Legally Sanctioned Same-Sex Marriage\"\n* '''For Release''', ''Minnesota Student Association'', 7&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971.\n* also, '''for immediate release''', ''FREE'', 17&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970.\n* and, '''News from''', ''Fight Repression of Erotic Expression'', 1&nbsp;November&nbsp;1969\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> interest in FREE expands quickly. Its \"leaders believe it to be the first such organization on a Big Ten campus\", the second such organization in the United States, following the [[Student Homophile League]]<ref>Merged later with the [[Columbia Queer Alliance]].</ref> recognized by [[Columbia University]] in 1967.<ref>{{cite news|last=Schumach|first=Murray|title=Columbia Charters Homosexual Group|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1967/05/03/107188654.pdf|accessdate=July 23, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=May 3, 1967}}</ref>\n\n'''1970''': Moving openly and aggressively, FREE slowly transforms [[Minneapolis]].<ref name=Coverage>On page&nbsp;13: \"A mecca for gays\", in a story by\n* Lily Hansen, ''GAY'', \"F.R.E.E. At Last\", 11&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970.  \n* also, \"Three big companies say they hire Gays\", ''The&nbsp;Advocate'', 30&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970.\n* and, Ken Bronson, \"A Quest for Full Equality\", 2004; [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf#page=9 available online] from ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* One member asks five major companies to explain their attitudes toward gay men and women.<ref name=Coverage /> Three large companies respond quickly, insisting that they did not discriminate against homosexuals in their hiring policies.<ref name=Coverage /> [[Honeywell]] objects:<ref name=Honeywell>An inquiry about employment of homosexuals generates a response from Gerry&nbsp;E. Morse, Vice President, ''Honeywell&nbsp;Inc.''. \n* See: letter to '''FREE''', addressed to James&nbsp;W. Chesebro, 29&nbsp;June&nbsp;1970.\n* and: Lars Bjornson, \"A quiet win: Honeywell yields\", ''The Advocate'', 10&nbsp;April&nbsp;1974, 13.\n* Courtesy: Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \"We would not employ a known homosexual.\" That member expands his surveys as complaints surface.\n\n* Another member is eager to educate his parents. For credit, he selects a program requested by Dave Moore, then a popular announcer on WCCO-TV. The student is proud of what ultimately airs on Sunday, 30&nbsp;September 1973.<ref>Review the FREE member's course work, including words to his parents.\n* Courtesy: \"Human Relations\", ''University Media Resources''\n* {{YouTube|id=mOwGW-Jie7E&feature=c4-overview&list=UU0ClfyXL_loos5QtXwPhMhQ|title=available online}}\n* Posted by Brandon Wolf </ref> \n\n* Members vote to endorse<ref name=FREE /> [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|\"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\"]].<ref name=memoir>Memoir of Michael McConnell, as told to Gail Langer Karwoski, \"The Wedding Heard 'Round the World: America's First Gay Marriage,\" ''University of Minnesota Press'', 2016</ref><ref name=Halfhill />\n\n'''1972''': FREE continues working with a faculty committee to craft a new policy that would protect gay students from discrimination.<ref name=policy>See: letter to Jack Baker et al., from\n* Malcolm Moos, President, ''University of Minnesota'', 11&nbsp;February&nbsp;1971.  \"I appreciate your willingness to serve on the Campus Committee on Placement Services\";\n* also: Gary Urban, \"Complaint charges Honeywell discrimination\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 12&nbsp;March&nbsp;1973, 8; \n* Courtesy: Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;1a&nbsp;-&nbsp;d], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> \n\n* '''May''': Central Administration approves a final draft.<ref name=policy /> \n\n* Campus Committee on Placement Services accepts complaints of unequal treatment by employers recruiting on campus. \n\n'''1974''': When faced with a denial of access to students, Honeywell \"quietly reverses its hiring policy\".<ref name=Honeywell /> No longer would it refuse to employ students who were openly gay.\n\n===Gay Pride===\n'''1971''': After the Stonewall Rebellion \u2013 New York City, 1969<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/04/us/stonewall-riots-gay-pride.html|title=50 Years Later, What We Forgot About Stonewall|last=Salam|first=Maya|date=2019-06-04|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-05|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nps.gov/ston/index.htm|title=Stonewall National Monument (U.S. National Park Service)|last=York|first=Mailing Address: 26 Wall Street Federal Hall National Monument c/o Stonewall National Monument New|last2=Us|first2=NY 10005 Phone: 212-668-2577 Contact|website=www.nps.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> \u2013 members of FREE from ''Gay&nbsp;House'' promote self-pride with picnics in Loring Park, near Downtown Minneapolis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.mnhs.org/cms/display?irn=10262356|title=Twin Cities Gay and Lesbian Community Oral History Project: Interview with Koreen Phelps : Collections Online : mnhs.org|website=collections.mnhs.org|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> Thom Higgins<ref name=Pride>A monk turned gay activist.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> crafts \"Gay Pride\" as a chant to discredit the two terms often condemned as \"sins\" by the Catholic archbishop for Minneapolis and Saint Paul. \n\n'''2018''': \"The wrenching bankruptcy that forced a reckoning on the Archdiocese of St. Paul and Minneapolis for decades of clergy sexual abuse has culminated in a $230 million settlement for roughly 450 victims, the largest of its kind nationwide.\"<ref>Victims' attorney Jeff Anderson is overcome with emotion.\n* Staff writers, \"$210 in Atonement\", ''Star&nbsp;Tribune'', 1&nbsp;June&nbsp;2018,&nbsp;A1\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\n===Student Body President===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Shoes poster 1971.tif|thumb|right|1971 election poster]]  -->\n'''1971''': Baker campaigned to become president of the Minnesota Student Association<ref name=\"Student Body President\">A student body president known by different names; elected 1971, re-elected 1972. \n* March&nbsp;1942: Richard John Baker, Certificate of Birth \n* September&nbsp;1969: Jack Baker, name adopted to lead activists demanding gay equality \n* August&nbsp;1971: Pat&nbsp;Lyn McConnell, married name; by Decree of Adoption \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''\n* also, Kay Tobin and Randy Wicker, \"The&nbsp;Gay Crusaders\", ''Paperback Library'', New&nbsp;York:&nbsp;1972, 136</ref> on the U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M's Minneapolis campus. \"''Student Control over Student Concerns''\",<ref name=Platform>Platform for student body president \n* Jack Baker, \"Policy Statement\", March&nbsp;1971\n* Endorsed by ''Minnesota Daily'', \"Baker for MSA president\", 5&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;page&nbsp;4. \"He has spoken truth to power because he knows the power of truth.\"\n* After graduation, the Governor signed into law a bill reserving one seat on the Board of Regents for an enrolled student.</ref> urged students \"to search out a new self-respect.\"<ref name=\"Student Body President\" /> Thoughtful posters with a focus on [https://box8661.blogspot.com/2013/06/marriage-equality-was-inevitable.htm self-pride] helped his election,<ref name=election>A total of 6,024 ballots cast topped the previous record of 5,049 in the 1958 election.\n* See: Steve Brandt, \"Baker wins in record vote,\" ''Minnesota Daily'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;1\n* and, Gary Dawson, \"Homosexual Credits U Election Victory to a New Sophistication\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Dispatch'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;35\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> and re-election. <ref name=re-election>It was \"the first time in the 121-year history of the U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M that a student body president has been re-elected.\"\n* See: Vic Stoner, \"Baker, Schwartz win MSA election\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 7&nbsp;April&nbsp;1972,&nbsp;1\n* and, Associated Press, \"Law senior elected U. student president\", ''Austin Daily Herald'', 7&nbsp;April&nbsp;1972,&nbsp;p.&nbsp;?\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref>\n\n* \"We need a student on the Board of Regents,\" he insisted. No need to wait for a new law.<ref name=Platform /> \"The Regents already have the power to appoint students to all committees of the Board or Regents.\" \n\n* Baker captured 2,766&nbsp;votes;<ref name=election /> two competitors and write-in candidates split the remainder. \n\n* As student body president, Baker continued to question why the Board of Regents ignored students when making its decisions. Soon, one non-voting student was invited to sit with the regents at each committee meeting.<ref name=Platform /> \n\n'''1972''': Re-elected with \"3,035 votes out of a record turnout of 7,441\"<ref name=re-election /> \u2013 41% in a 3-way race.\n\n== Same-sex marriage activism ==\n\n===Lawsuit to obtain a licence===\n{{Main|Baker v. Nelson}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:McConnell (l) and Baker (r) apply for marriage license 19700518.png|thumb|right|Michael McConnell (l) and Jack Baker (18&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970) - by R. Bertrand Heine, Minnesota&nbsp;Historical&nbsp;Society]]  -->\n\n'''1970''': Minnesota's statutes do not explicitly forbid marriage between two adult men.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> Baker, a law student, argues that \"[[Everything which is not forbidden is allowed|what is not forbidden is permitted]]\"<ref>Jack Baker, as told to Helen Barrett, \"We had America's first gay marriage - in 1971\", ''Financial Times Magazine'', 7&nbsp;August&nbsp;2015; [https://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9d35d5d8-3ae4-11e5-bbd1-b37bc06f590c.html available online]</ref> when the couple applies for a marriage license in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> The Clerk of District Court<ref>18 May: Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; [[Hennepin County Government Center|Hennepin County]], Minnesota</ref>, Gerald Nelson, denies their request. Refusal by the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Facts_and_trial|lower courts]] to order Nelson to issue a license<ref>All claims were dismissed.\n* See: Associated Press, \"Marriage Is Out\", ''Kansas&nbsp;City Star'', 24&nbsp;May&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;30A\n* and, \"Gay Marriage Plea Is Denied\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer Press'', 19&nbsp;November&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;27\n* and, \"Court Won't Let Men Wed\", ''N.Y.&nbsp;Times'', 10&nbsp;Jan.&nbsp;1971, 65\n* also, Appellant's Jurisdictional Statement, ''[[Baker_v._Nelson]]'', Minnesota Supreme Court docket no.&nbsp;71-1027, at 3&nbsp;-&nbsp;4 (statement of the case)</ref> is affirmed by the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|Minnesota Supreme Court]].<ref>\"The institution of marriage as a union of man and woman, uniquely involving the procreation or rearing of children within a family, is as old as the book of Genesis\".\n* \"Opinion\", by Justice C.&nbsp;Donald Peterson, ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'', 15&nbsp;Oct&nbsp;1971, 191&nbsp;N.W.2d&nbsp;185 at&nbsp;186.</ref>\n\n* Leadership inside the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] shows \"little or no enthusiasm\" for support.<ref>Letter from Norman Dorsen (General Counsel for ''ACLU'' in 1970),\n* published by Jason Smith, \"Gay Pride Block Party Case\", ''Friends of the Bill of Rights Foundation'', January&nbsp;2012,&nbsp;52 \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/pdf/rare/gayprideblockparty.pdf#page=54 available online]\n* Courtesy: ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Court rules in effect allow the '''''Minnesota Civil Liberties Union''''' to appeal Minnesota's \"opinion\" directly to the [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|U.S. Supreme Court]].<ref name=NYT051715>{{cite news |last=Eckholm |first=Eric|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|accessdate=May 17, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2015}}</ref>  \n\n* Allan Spear, a U&nbsp;of&nbsp;M professor of history, describes them as the \"lunatic fringe\".<ref>David von Drehle, \"Gay Marriage Already Won\", ''TIME'', 8&nbsp;April&nbsp;2013,&nbsp;22</ref>  \n\n* The case receives extensive media attention,<ref name=letters+>See, a matrix of items (late 1960s, 1970s, early 1980),\n* especially, Jack Star, \"The Homosexual Couple,\" ''LOOK'', 26&nbsp;January&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;69&nbsp;-&nbsp;71\n* and, Michael Durham, \"Homosexuals in revolt\", ''LIFE'', 31&nbsp;December&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;68\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Gift&nbsp;#6, the marriage that made history\", Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> including appearances on the ''[[Phil Donahue Show]]'',<ref name=comdon>{{cite news |last=Condon |first=Patrick|title=Minn. gay couple in '71 marriage case still joined|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2012/12/10/news/jack-baker-michael-mcconnell-same-sex-marriage|accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=Minnesota Public Radio|date=December 10, 2012}}</ref> and Kennedy&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;Co. (WLS-TV, Chicago&nbsp;IL). On the ''[[David Susskind Show]]''<ref>[http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2013/05/15/old-video Available online] from Sasha Aslanian, \"Gay rights pioneers Jack Baker and Michael McConnell predicted marriage victory in '70s\", ''Minnesota Public Radio'' (16&nbsp;May&nbsp;2013)</ref> (New&nbsp;York,&nbsp;NY), Baker is blunt.<ref name=Bowes /> \"We're gonna win eventually, not this time but maybe the next time around.\" \n\n'''1972''': The clerk for Justice Harry Blackmun crafts a one-sentence rejection because \"I just [didn't] think the court was ready at the time to take on the issue.\"<ref>Jess Bravin, \"Supreme Court Clerk Remembers First Same-Sex Marriage Case\", ''The Wall Street Journal'', 1&nbsp;May&nbsp;2015; [https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-clerk-remembers-first-same-sex-marriage-case-1430494015 available online]</ref> A quick dismissal of ''[[Baker v. Nelson]]'' is approved unanimously.<ref name=greenhouse /> \n\n'''2015''': The high court allows lower courts to supervise a national debate before deciding that its decision to dismiss demands for marriage equality must be overruled.<ref>\"The Court now holds that same-sex couples may exercise the fundamental right to marry.\"\n* ''Obergefell&nbsp;v. Hodges,'' 26&nbsp;June&nbsp;2015, at&nbsp;22-23 \n* [https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/14pdf/14-556_3204.pdf#page=28 available online]</ref>\n\n* Gay Marriage is \"rejected by early gay activists [in New&nbsp;York City] who were mostly interested in sexual freedom and gay liberation.\"<ref>Thomas Kraemer, \"Jack Baker deserves mainstream press coverage after gay marriage ruling\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', 7&nbsp;July&nbsp;2012; [http://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2012/07/jack-baker-deserves-mainstream-press.html available online]</ref>\n\n* Gay \"historians\" ignore Minnesota because they \"personally had political objections to gay marriage activism.\"<ref>Minnesotans document gay history:\n* See: Thomas Kraemer [Professor], \"Gay marriage pioneer Jack Baker starts blog\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', 4&nbsp;April&nbsp;2012; [https://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2012/04/gay-marriage-pioneer-jack-baker-starts.html available online]\n* also, Jack Baker [Attorney], \"A court corrupted\"; [https://box8661.blogspot.com/2015/03/a-court-corrupted.html available online]</ref>\n\n===A civil right===\nIn 1970, [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|McConnell and Baker]] apply for a license to marry. The Clerk of District Court<ref>18 May: Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; Hennepin County, Minnesota</ref> rejects their request.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> McConnell re-applies in a different county and receives a marriage license.<ref>16&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971: Clerk of District Court, Fifth Judicial District, in Mankato \n* 3 September: At a ceremony in Minneapolis, Hennepin County, a United Methodist minister certifies the marriage contract.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder #7], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> Their wedding is proclaimed to be [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|\"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\"]].<ref name=memoir /> Assistant Chief Judge Gregory Anderson rules (2018) that \"The marriage is declared to be in all respects valid.\"<ref name=ruling>McConnells against Blue Earth County, \u201cCONCLUSIONS OF LAW\u201d, Fifth Judicial District, File&nbsp;#07-CV-16-4559, 18&nbsp;September&nbsp;2018. \n* \"The September&nbsp;3,&nbsp;1971 marriage of James&nbsp;Michael McConnell and Pat&nbsp;Lyn McConnell, a/k/a Richard&nbsp;John Baker, has never been dissolved or annulled by judicial decree and no grounds currently exist on which to invalidate the marriage.\" \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/McConnellvBlueEarthCounty-17-Sept-2018-ConclusionsofLaw_ORDER.pdf#page=4 Available online] from U of Minnesota Libraries.\n* Courtesy: McConnell&nbsp;Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder&nbsp;#4], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref>\n\nBaker is invited to address members of the Ramsey County Bar Association. Same-sex unions are \"not only authorized by the U.S. Constitution\"<ref>Bob Protzman, \"Gay Marriage OK Predicted\", ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer&nbsp;Press'', 22&nbsp;October&nbsp;1971, p&nbsp;?</ref> but are mandatory, he explains. \"I&nbsp;am convinced that same-sex marriages will be legalized in the United States.\"\n\n'''1972''': Baker speaks to a forum of more than 2,000 at the [[University of Winnipeg]]. \"We maintain that it's a matter of equity and fair play that if a state is going to give childless heterosexual couples rights and benefits under the law, they can't complain when childless same-sex couples ask for the same rights.\"<ref name=\"Canada\">Persistence spread first to Canada, than worldwide.\n* See: Jack Baker, \"The right to be human and gay\", ''Manitoban'', 13&nbsp;March&nbsp;1972,\n* as reprinted by Ken Bronson in \"A Quest for Full Equality\", 2004, 69,  \n* [https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf#page=73 available online] from ''University  of Minnesota Libraries'';\n* also, Mia Rabson, \"Couple helped make history\", ''Winnipeg Free&nbsp;Press'', 17&nbsp;September&nbsp;2004, A4 and \n* letter from Rich North to Jack [Baker] & Mike [McConnell], 20&nbsp;September&nbsp;2004); [http://box8661.blogspot.com/2012/04/letter-from-canada-2.html available online].\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;6a&nbsp;-&nbsp;b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> The lecture persuades Richard North to begin a \"fight to be married\" to Chris Vogel.<ref name=Canada /> His persistence leads to marriage equality in [[Canada]] during 2004.<ref name= Canada />\n\n'''2012''': Demands for same-sex marriage continue to grow worldwide, becoming \"the civil rights issue of our times\".<ref name=\"never in doubt\">Lecture by NAACP President Benjamin Todd Jealous, during a news conference at the organization's national headquarters.\n* Michael&nbsp;K. Lavers, \"NAACP president: Marriage is '''civil rights issue of our times'''\" ''Washington Blade'', 21&nbsp;May&nbsp;2012; [http://www.washingtonblade.com/2012/05/21/naacp-president-marriage-is-civil-rights-issue-of-our-times/ available online]\n* also, Patrick Condon, \"Gay couple in 1971 marriage ruling reflect on new court challenges\", ''Associated Press,'' as reprinted in the ''St.&nbsp;Paul Pioneer&nbsp;Press'', 11&nbsp;December&nbsp;2012, 3A+.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;7a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> Speaking to the ''Associated Press'', Baker explained that the \"outcome was never in doubt because the conclusion was intuitively obvious to a first-year law student.\"<ref name=\"never in doubt\" /> Same-sex marriage is [[Baker_v._Nelson|legalized nationwide]] in 2015.\n\n=== Adoption, name change, marriage ===\nIn 1971, McConnell legally adopts<ref>FINDINGS AND DECREE [File No.&nbsp;AD-19962], 3&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971\n* Order signed by Judge Lindsay&nbsp;G. Arthur, Juvenile Division\n* Fourth Judicial District, in Minneapolis; Hennepin County, Minnesota\n* See: Anon., \"U student head adopted by homosexual friend\", ''Minneapolis Tribune'', 25&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;1A\n* also, Associated Press, \"Male's adoption by roommate OKd\", ''Rocky Mountain News'', Denver, 26&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;85\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder&nbsp;#3, file&nbsp;#2], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Baker because \"regardless of popular conception, adoption is not limited to children\". Baker's legal name changes to Pat Lyn McConnell. They visit friends in [[Mankato]] where McConnell applies and receives a marriage license.<ref name=\"Free Press\">Issued by the Clerk of District Court, in [[Mankato]], Fifth Judicial District, [[Blue Earth County]] \n* See: \"Daily Record\", ''Mankato&nbsp;Free Press'', 16&nbsp;August&nbsp;1971, p.&nbsp;?\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [binder&nbsp;#7], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> The Rev. Roger Lynn, a [[United Methodist]] minister, validates their marriage contract.<ref name=Bowes>\"Pastor Roger Lynn holds up Baker and McConnell's marriage certificate\"\n* Claire Bowes, \"Jack Baker and Michael McConnell: Gay&nbsp;Americans who married in 1971\", ''BBC&nbsp;News Magazine'', 3&nbsp;July&nbsp;2013 \n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23159390 available online]. \n* A United Methodist minister officiated at a ceremony in Minneapolis, Hennepin County.</ref><ref name=FREE /> \n\n'''1972''': The Hennepin County Attorney convenes a grand jury, which \"studied the legality of the marriage but found the question not worth pursuing.\"<ref>\"Thus the marriage remained in effect.\"\n* See: \"Homosexual Wins Fight to Take Bar Examination in Minnesota\", ''New York Times'', 7&nbsp;January&nbsp;1973, 55. </ref>\n\n'''1974''': ''The&nbsp;Family Law Reporter''<ref name=FLR>Anon., \"Gay married couple frustrated in adoption bid\", ''The&nbsp;Family Law Reporter'', published by The&nbsp;Bureau of National Affairs, 10&nbsp;December&nbsp;1974, page&nbsp;2103</ref> argues that the \"federal constitution prohibition against ex post facto laws .&nbsp;.&nbsp;. forbids the imposition of punishment for past conduct lawful at the time it was engaged\".<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> Hence, the Minnesota high court's opinion \u2013 ''[[ Baker v. Nelson]]'' \u2013 does not reach back to Baker and McConnell because the two were married \"a full six weeks\" before that decision.\n\n'''2013''': Thomas Kraemer, a retired professor at [[Oregon State University]], concludes that &nbsp;FREE hosted \"the first same-sex couple in history to be legally married\".<ref name=Kraemer>Thomas Kraemer [professor, Oregon State University], \"Gay marriage discussion in 1953 vs.&nbsp;1963 and today\", ''Tom's&nbsp;OSU'', posted 16&nbsp;December&nbsp;2013; [http://tomsosu.blogspot.com/2013/12/gay-marriage-discussion-in-1953-vs-1963.html available online]</ref> Records at ''The National Archives''<ref name=Archives>Anon., \"Hidden Treasures from the Stacks: pushing for equality\", ''The&nbsp;National Archives at Kansas City'', September&nbsp;2013, 7; [https://www.archives.gov/kansas-city/press/newsletter/2013-september.pdf#page=7 available online]</ref> verify that \"McConnell and Baker's marriage license [from Blue&nbsp;Earth County, MN] was never revoked. They are still married and have been for the last forty two years.\"\n\n=== Federal courts respond ===\nValidity of the marriage depends on how Minnesota's [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|marriage law]] is interpreted.<ref name=\"Marriage law\" /> A direct appeal to the United States Supreme Court is [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|dismissed]].<ref>409 U.S. 810, 93&nbsp;S.Ct.&nbsp;37, 34&nbsp;L.Ed.2d&nbsp;65&nbsp;(1972)</ref> While an appeal to the Minnesota Supreme Court is pending, McConnell re-applies and obtains a [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#Adoption,_name_change,_marriage|marriage license]].<ref name=\"Free Press\" /> By ORDER of Assistant Chief Judge Gregory Anderson, \"The marriage is declared to be in all respects valid.\"<ref name=ruling />\n\n'''1971''': Both state and federal courts reject the marriage, others approve.<ref>\"What is believed to be the first same-sex marriage in the United States was performed in Minnesota.\"\n* Courtesy: Pat Kessler, \"A Rare Glimpse At Minn.'s 1st Gay Wedding In 1971\", ''WCCO'' [CBS, Minnesota], 31&nbsp;July&nbsp;2013; [http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/07/29/a-rare-glimpse-at-minns-1st-gay-wedding-in-1971/ available online].\n* also, Naomi Pescovitz, \"Pastor Reflects Back on Minn. Gay Marriage\", ''KSTP-TV'' [Minneapolis,&nbsp;MN], 16&nbsp;May&nbsp;2013; {{YouTube|5MdGM9xBIMQ|available online}}.\n* and, Associated Press, \"They're Mr. and Mr.\", ''San Francisco Chronicle'', 8&nbsp;September&nbsp;1971,&nbsp;3</ref> \n\n'''1973''': A joint tax return for 1973 is rejected by the Internal Revenue Service.<ref>Anon., \"Homosexual Couple Contest I.R.S. Ban On a Joint Return\", ''The&nbsp;New York Times'', 5&nbsp;Jan.&nbsp;1975,&nbsp;55</ref>\n\n'''1974''': McConnell lists Baker as an [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#Adoption,_name_change,_marriage|adopted \"child\"]] on his tax returns from 1974 through 2004 for which he claims a deduction as [[head of household]]. That benefit ends when Congress limits the deduction for an adopted child under the age of 19.<ref>Anon., \"Form 1040 Instructions\", ''Internal Revenue Service'' (2005), 19; [https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-prior/i1040gi--2005.pdf#page=19 available online]</ref>\n\n'''1976''': A claim filed with the Veterans Administration is rejected<ref>''McConnell v. Nooner'':\n* District Court: No.&nbsp;4-75-Civ.&nbsp;566 (D.&nbsp;Minn. 20&nbsp;April&nbsp;1976)\n* and, United States Court of Appeals, Eighth Circuit: 547&nbsp;F.2d&nbsp;54 (8th&nbsp;Cir.&nbsp;1976)</ref> because \"Minnesota law prohibits same sex marriages<ref>[[Baker_v._Nelson]], 291&nbsp;Minn.&nbsp;310, 191&nbsp;N.W.2d&nbsp;185&nbsp;(1971)</ref> .&nbsp;.&nbsp;.\"\n\n==Employment discrimination==\nThe University Librarian offers Michael McConnell the position of Head of the Cataloging Division at the library on the St.&nbsp;Paul campus.<ref name=\"job offer\"> '''1970''': Letter to Michael McConnell,\n* from Ralph&nbsp;H. Hopp, University Librarian, ''University of Minnesota'' [Minneapolis], 27&nbsp;April;\n* also, see Randy Tigue, \"Regent: FREE&nbsp;member case is a matter of public&nbsp;relations\", ''Minnesota Daily'', 16&nbsp;July,&nbsp;1;\n* and, letter from James&nbsp;F. Hogg, Secretary, Board of Regents, ''University of Minnesota'', 10&nbsp;July. \"... your conduct, as represented in the public and University news media, is not consistent with the best interest of the University.\" \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;5a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> After McConnell applies for a marriage license, regent&nbsp;Daniel Gainey insists that \"homosexuality is about the worst thing there is.\" \n\n'''1970''': The Board of Regents rejects the offer. McConnell sues in federal [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/316/809/1951718/ <span style=\"color:blue\">District Court</span>] and prevails.<ref>Bob Lundegaard, \"University Ordered to Hire Homosexual\", ''Minneapolis Tribune'', 10&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970,&nbsp;23</ref>\n\n'''1971''': The Board appeals to the [https://openjurist.org/451/f2d/193/mcconnell-v-anderson <span style=\"color:blue\">Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals.</span>]<ref>Anon., \"Homosexual Wins a Suit over Hiring\", ''New York Times'', 20&nbsp;September&nbsp;1970; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1970/09/20/355908502.pdf available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref> The panel concludes that the University did not restrict free speech. Instead, it was McConnell who wants \"to pursue an activist role in implementing his controversial ideas concerning the social status to be accorded homosexuals and thereby to foist tacit approval of the socially repugnant concept upon his employer.\"<ref>Michelle Andrea Wolf and Alfred P. Kielwasser, eds., \"Gay People, Sex, and the Media\", ''Haworth Press'' (1991), 237; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Y_Hd0F2J7LEC&pg=PA237& available online], accessed February 7, 2012</ref>\n\n'''1972''': More than 80% of the student body voice disapproval of the regents' action.<ref>\"Do you think the University was justified in firing McConnell because of his open declaration of homosexuality?\"\n* yes&nbsp;=&nbsp;10%, no&nbsp;=&nbsp;81%, no opinion&nbsp;=&nbsp;8%, other&nbsp;=&nbsp;1%\n* See: Office of Student Affairs, \"Research Bulletin\", ''University of Minnesota'', Winter&nbsp;1972  \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes&nbsp;5a&nbsp;-&nbsp;e], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> McConnell is hired by the [[Hennepin County Library]].<ref>1972: Then, a diverse and growing system of 26&nbsp;facilities; \n* he rises to the level of Coordinating Librarian before retiring.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volumes 6a-b], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> When he retires 37&nbsp;years later, the Board of Commissioners commends him for his service.<ref>See: \"Item&nbsp;7A - Commendation of Michael McConnell\", ''Hennepin County Board of Commissioners'', 30&nbsp;November&nbsp;2010; [http://hennepinmn.granicus.com/MediaPlayer.php?view_id=10&amp;clip_id=1134 available online].</ref>\n\n'''2012''': University president [[Eric Kaler]] offers McConnell an apology for the \"reprehensible\" treatment he endured from the Board of Regents in 1970.<ref>2012: \"News\", ''University News Service'', 22&nbsp;June\n* 2018: President Kaler affirmed his 2012 News statements. Action taken by our Board in 1970, he said, \"is today worthy of deep criticism - of rebuke and censure.\" See: Email to Logan Chelmo, 27&nbsp;June&nbsp;2018; class of 2018, Shakopee High School, located in Shakopee, Minnesota\n* 2020: McConnell is enrolled as a member of the Heritage Society of the President's Club. See: Letter from xxx, 6&nbsp;June&nbsp;2020  \n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder #7, MEMORANDUM for the record], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> McConnell accepts his assurance that \"such practices would not be consistent with the practices enforced today at the university.\"<ref>Gift&nbsp;#1 is accepted by Kristin Lockhart, Associate Vice President for Equity and Diversity, 25&nbsp;July.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"America\u2019s First Gay Marriage\" [Binder&nbsp;#8], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref>\n\n==Career in law and politics==\nIn June 1972, Baker led the DFL Gay Rights Caucus<ref>'''For Release Any Time''', \"Gay Machine Startles DFL Regulars\", ''DFL Gay Rights Caucus'', 9&nbsp;June&nbsp;1972.</ref> at the State Convention of the [[Minnesota Democratic\u2013Farmer\u2013Labor Party]]. When the caucus proposed \"legislation defining marriage as a civil contract between any two adults\",<ref>Resolution&nbsp;71.d, \"The 1972 DFL Platform\", ''Minnesota Democratic-Farmer-Labor State Central Committee'', 9&nbsp;-&nbsp;11&nbsp;June&nbsp;1972 at Rochester, MN.</ref> the delegates approved that wording for inclusion in the party platform. This was the first time a major United States political party encouraged support for marriage equality.\n\nAfter he graduated from the [[University of Minnesota Law School]] in December,<ref>Malcolm Moos, President, ''University of Minnesota'', 13&nbsp;December&nbsp;1972: \"The Degree Of Juris Doctor With All Its Privileges And Obligations\" is conferred</ref> his request to take the bar examination raised questions of fraud surrounding his [[Timeline_of_same-sex_marriage#1970s|1971 marriage license]]. At a hearing, Baker was defended by the Minnesota Civil Liberties Union.<ref>Anon., \"Marriage hurdle cleared, Baker to take bar exams\", ''Minneapolis Star'', 28&nbsp;December 1972,&nbsp;2</ref> He was admitted to the bar<ref> October 2002: In a MEMO for the record, Baker explains why lobbying by the Chief Justice, Oscar Knutson, failed to deny him a license to practice law.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;7a, section&nbsp;II], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''.</ref> after the State Board of Law Examiners reviewed the facts and concluded that he was entitled to take the exam.<ref name=bar>{{cite news|title=Homosexual Wins Fights to Take Bar Examination in Minnesota|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1973/01/07/119453382.pdf |accessdate=March 20, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=January 7, 1973}}</ref> \n\nBaker campaigned for Associate Justice of the Minnesota Supreme Court five times. He argued that each opponent violated the Code of Judicial Conduct<ref name=\"Results\">Jack Baker questioned why some judges were allowed to ignore the Code of Judicial Conduct.\n* 1970: Canon&nbsp;5E. '''Arbitration'''. \"A judge should not act as an arbitrator or mediator.\" \n* 1994: Canon&nbsp;4F. '''Service as Arbitrator or Mediator'''. \"A judge shall not act as an arbitrator or mediator or otherwise perform judicial functions in a private capacity unless expressly authorized by law.\"\n* 1978: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=72 C. Donald Peterson]\n* 1980: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=73 George M. Scott]\n* 1982: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=74 John E. Simonett]\n* 1984: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=74 Douglas K. Amdahl]\n* 2002: [http://www.minnesotalegalhistoryproject.org/assets/Election%20Results%201857-2016.pdf#page=84 Paul H. Anderson]\n* others\n* Courtesy: Douglas A. Hedrin, \"Results of Elections of Justices to the Minnesota Supreme Court 1857-2016\", ''Minnesota Legal History Project''\n* Details: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> by heading the [[C._Donald_Peterson#Minnesota News Council|Minnesota News Council]] (MNC). \n\nEthics of C. Donald Peterson were questioned in 1978, George Scott in 1980, John Simonett<ref>See: Initial Annual Registration for a Minnesota Non-Profit Corporation, ''Office of the Secretary of State''. \n* \"Effective August 1, 1989, all non-profit corporations are now required to file an annual registration once every calendar year. Please review the information on the label and read all directions before completing this form.\"\n* Corporate Charter Number: L-559 \n* Corporate Name: Minnesota News Council \n* [[Registered Office]] Address: '''230&nbsp;State&nbsp;Capital''', St.&nbsp;Paul, MN [chambers of the Minnesota Supreme Court before moving to a new location] \n* Signature: [Associate Justice] '''John&nbsp;E. Simonett''' \n* Title of Office: Chair \n* Date: 1/22/90\n* Courtesy: ''Minnesota Historical Society''</ref> in 1982, Douglas Amdahl in 1984 and [[Paul H. Anderson]] in 2002. In the ''Plebiscite'' mailed to more than 14,900 attorneys in Minnesota, Baker challenged the bar to end special relationships between Justices of Minnesota's Supreme Court and MNC.<ref name=\"rule_of_law\">Jack Baker, \"2002 Judicial '''Plebiscite'''\", ''Minnesota State Bar Association'', September&nbsp;2002\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> Nevertheless, collusion continued.<ref>The list of \"Supreme Court Justices who chaired the News Council\"\n* 1971-80: C. Donald Peterson\n* [also: George M. Scott]\n* 1980-82: Douglas K. Amdahl\n* 1982-94: John E. Simonett\n* 1995-97: Paul H. Anderson\n* 1998-2006: Edward Stringer\n* See: email from Susan Hansen, <newscncl@mtn.org>, 14 June 2000.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume 7a], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, University of Minnesota Libraries</ref> \n\nBenefits bestowed on a judge who ignored the Code of Judicial Conduct and who [[C._Donald_Peterson#Minnesota News Council|helped to mediate]] private disputes continued even after the MNC was ejected from court chambers in 1994.<ref>Remaining offices for the Minnesota Supreme Court moved from 230&nbsp;State&nbsp;Capitol in January\n* \u201cEmployees coped. They moved into the newly remodeled space floor-by-floor and coexisted with construction over a period of time from September through '''December''' [1994].\u201d\n* See: Roland C. Amundson, \u201cA Search for Place: The History of the Minnesota Judicial Center\u201d, ''Minnesota Court of Appeals'', 1995,&nbsp;67.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref><ref>Not until James H. Gilbert resigned as Associate Justice and was hired by MNC in 2007 as its \"Hearing Chair\" did MNC stop recruiting judges to mediate its disputes.\n* See: email from Sarah E. Bauer, Interim Director, Minnesota News Council, 11&nbsp;May&nbsp;2007;\n* new address: '''12&nbsp;South Sixth&nbsp;Street''', Suite&nbsp;927, Minneapolis, MN&nbsp;55402.\n* Courtesy: McConnell Files, \"Full Equality, a diary\" [volume&nbsp;8c], Tretter Collection in GLBT Studies, ''University of Minnesota Libraries''</ref> MNC ceased to exist in 2011.<ref>Gail Rosenblum, \"News council's demise is bad news for all who value the truth\", ''Star&nbsp;Tribune'', 23&nbsp;February 2011, B1</ref>\n\n==Later years==\n[[File:BakerMcConnell.jpg|thumb|Baker and McConnell in 2016]]\nIn 2003, Baker and McConnell amended their individual tax returns for the year 2000, filing jointly as a couple. They offered proof of a valid marriage license issued in Blue Earth County. The IRS challenged the validity of the marriage license and argued that, even if the license were valid, the [[Defense of Marriage Act]] prohibited the IRS from recognizing it. When McConnell brought suit, the [[United States District Court for the District of Minnesota|U.S. District Court for Minnesota]] upheld the IRS ruling<ref>{{cite web|title=McConnell v. United States, January 3, 2005|url=http://www.lawprofessorblogs.com/taxprof/linkdocs/2005-1056-1.pdf|publisher=US District Court for Minnesota|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref> and the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals affirmed, saying that McConnell could not re-litigate the question decided in ''[[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_Minnesota_Supreme_Court|Baker v. Nelson]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=McConnell v. United States, July 17, 2006|url=http://docs.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca8/05-1781/051781u-2011-02-25.pdf?1301253248|publisher=8th Circuit Court of Appeals|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. Supreme Court agreed in 2015, \"to decide the issue Jack Baker and Mike McConnell tried to bring before it in 1972: Do same-sex couples have a constitutional right to get married?\"<ref>Roger Parloff, \"12 key moments that led to the Supreme Court's same-sex marriage case\", ''fortune.com'' (posted 16&nbsp;January&nbsp;2015); [http://fortune.com/2015/01/18/same-sex-marriage-supreme-court/ available online]</ref> Though [[Baker_v._Nelson#Appeal_to_the_U.S._Supreme_Court|that case was dismissed]] \"for want of a substantial federal question\",<ref name=greenhouse>{{cite news |last=Greenhouse |first=Linda |title=Wedding Bells|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/03/20/wedding-bells/|accessdate=March 21, 2013|newspaper=New York Times|date=March 20, 2013}}</ref> the couple obtained a [[Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker#A_civil_right|legal marriage license]] before the appeal began. Minnesota's Attorney General argued, as a friend of the court: \"The procreation rationale [used by the Minnesota Supreme Court] does not support the prohibition of same-sex marriage\".<ref name=swanson>Lori Swanson, Attorney General, State of Minnesota; \"Brief of the State of Minnesota as AMICUS CURIAE in support of petitioners\", Obergefell v. Hodges; ''In The Supreme Court of the United States'', March&nbsp;2015, 18; [http://thecolu.mn/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/MNSCOTUSbrief.pdf#page=30 available online]</ref>\n\nBaker and McConnell were still living as a married couple as late as May 2015.<ref name=NYT051715>{{cite news |last=Eckholm |first=Eric|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|accessdate=May 17, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 16, 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:MikeMcConnell.jpg|thumb|right|upright|McConnell in 2016]]\n\n==Interview==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2015/07/16/baker-mcconnell|title=For Mpls. couple, gay marriage ruling is a victory 43 years in the making|author=Tom Crann|date=16 July 2015|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio News}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-06-25/meet-two-men-who-managed-get-first-known-same-sex-marriage-license-back-1970|title=Meet the two men who managed to get the first known same-sex marriage license - back in 1970|author=T.J. Raphael|date=25 June 2015|publisher=The Takeaway, Public Radio International}}\n\n==Short documentary==\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cse4s3gmbPE|title=Baker v. Nelson: The Original Case for Gay Marriage|author=Joseph Kase and Jeremiah Smith|date=Feb 2014|publisher=YouTube}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/07/29/a-rare-glimpse-at-minns-1st-gay-wedding-in-1971/|title=A Rare Glimpse At Minn.'s 1st Gay Wedding In 1971|author=Pat Kessler|date=29 July 2013|publisher=WCCO-TV, Minneapolis}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/17/us/the-same-sex-couple-who-got-a-marriage-license-in-1971.html|title=The Same-Sex Couple Who Got a Marriage License in 1971|author= Erik Eckholm|date=16 May 2015|publisher=www.nytimes.com|newspaper=The New York Times}}\n* {{cite magazine|url=http://time.com/3843579/influential-marriages/|title=The 25 Most Influential Marriages of All Time|author=Lisa Grunwald|date=12 May 2015|magazine=TIME}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.qlibrary.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Seeds_for_Gay_Marriage_Equality.pdf#page=2|title=Who defined the gay agenda?|author=Pat Lyn McConnell|date=Jan 2014|publisher=[[Quatrefoil Library]]}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23159390|title=Jack Baker and Michael McConnell: Gay Americans who married in 1971|author=Claire Bowes|date=4 July 2013|accessdate=4 July 2013|work=BBC News}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.qlibrary.org/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Quatrefolio-2012-Pride.pdf#page=5|title=Minnesota Led the Two Coasts on Marriage Rights, and Should Do So Again: Jack Baker and Michael McConnell|author=Robert Frame|year=2012|publisher=Quatrefoil Library}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.lib.umn.edu/sites/default/files/media/Quest%20copy.pdf|title=A Quest for Full Equality|author=Ken Bronson|year=2004|publisher=University of Minnesota Libraries}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.brumm.com/schools/gaylib/earlybrumm.html#baker|title=My Own Early Gay History|author=Dennis Brumm|year=1971|publisher=www.brumm.com}}\n* Memoir of Michael McConnell (2016) as told to Gail Langer Karwoski, [http://www.worldcat.org/title/wedding-heard-round-the-world-americas-first-gay-marriage/oclc/926312828&referer=brief_results \"The Wedding Heard Heard 'Round the World: America's First Gay Marriage.\"], Minneapolis, MN: ''University of Minnesota Press''.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baker, Jack}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Minnesota]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Y6f&tP4z", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater years", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_McConnell_and_Jack_Baker"}
